<HEADLINE> No Plan to Negotiate Gas Supply to Israel: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Oil Minister Hamdi
Al-Banbi said Wednesday that Egypt has no plans to negotiate
natural gas supply to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Al-Banbi's words came in response to the statements by Israeli
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon Tuesday that talks will be
held for importing natural gas from Egypt, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
All gas produced by the Egyptian General Petroleum Corporation
(EGPC) is being consumed domestically and Egypt plans to buy more
from international companies operating in the country, Al-Banbi
said.
</P>
<P>
The EGPC has signed a number of agreements with foreign
companies to buy gas in the years to come to meet increasing
domestic demands for natural gas, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said international companies working in Egypt,
including the U.S. Amoco and the Italy's Agip, have been trying
for years to secure their shares in the world market.
</P>
<P>
They have been in contact with several countries in the region,
including Israel, Al-Banbi said. The two companies have received
positive responses from all the states except Israel, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharon, also foreign minister, has prevented Israel's
electricity suppliers from contacting the companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel in 1979, maintains cold ties with the Jewish state due to
Israel's intransigence in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have few business or economic ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
