<HEADLINE> Money Supply Growth in Euroland Remains Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Two days before the launch of the
single euro currency in 11 "Euroland" countries, the latest data
showed money supply growth in the 11 countries remaining within
moderate limits.
</P>
<P>
The European Central Bank (ECB) in Frankfurt said on Wednesday
that the money supply showed 4.5 percent annual growth in
November, compared with 5.0 percent in October and 4.5 percent in
September. The average for the three months was 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The data showed that monetary expansion was "very close to the
reference value of 4.5 percent" which the ECB board of governors
had set during their December 1 meeting.
</P>
<P>
In absolute terms, the money supply in the 11 Euroland
countries - all 15 European Union members except for Britain,
Greece, Denmark and Sweden - came to just under 4.33 trillion ECUs
(5.07 trillion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
