<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Opposes Missile Deployment on Greek Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem said here Wednesday that Turkey opposes the possible
deployment of the Russian-made S-300 missiles on the Crete island
of Greece.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Cem said that the deployment of
the surface-to-air missiles in Crete, rather than on Cyprus within
the framework of "joint aggression doctrine" between Greece and
the Greek Cypriot side, will add a new problem to the already
problematic relations between Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey does not consider the missiles an issue of bargaining,
even negotiation in this regard is out of the question, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides announced Tuesday that he
had decided not to deploy the S-300 missiles in Cyprus and would
negotiate with Russia on possible deployment of the missiles in
Crete.
</P>
<P>
Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis said on Tuesday that his
country supported Clerides' decision.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus struck the missile deal with Russia in January 1997, in
a bid to cement its air defense capability.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, the close ally of independence-seeking Turkish Cypriots
in northern Cyprus, has threatened to launch preemptive strikes on
the missiles if they are brought to the divided island.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the missiles in Cyprus had already been put off
several times under Turkish and international pressures.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north after Turkey landed
its troops on and took over the northern third of the country in
1984 in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
