<HEADLINE> U.S. Fires Missiles Again on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S.
administration official confirmed on Wednesday that U.S. fighter
planes fired missiles and laser-guided bombs on a defense site
in southern Iraq early in the day after a British warplane
observed six to eight missiles being fired from the Iraq missile
site.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton is to be briefed by National Security
Council advisers later on Wednesday, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a Pentagon official said a British Bomber reported the
activity at about 9:30 a.m. local time (0630 GMT) southwest of
Talil, Iraq, and observed that there were several surface-to-air
missiles fired from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Two U.S. F-16 fighter planes patrolling the area responded
and fired two HARM anti-radar missiles and a number of
precision-guided bombs onto the site at 10:15 a.m. local time
(0715 GMT). The Pentagon official said that "there is no
assessment of the damage."
</P>
<P>
The aircraft safely returned to their bases in southwest
Asia about a half hour later.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman David Leavy said that U.S. and British
aircraft "will continue to enforce the no-fly zones vigorously,"
"as the president has said, they are a key element of our
containment policy."
</P>
<P>
It was the second clash this week between U.S. and Iraqi
forces in the northern and southern Iraqi no-fly zones, which
Baghdad has declared illegal and does not recognize.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, U.S. warplanes exchanged missile fire with Iraqi air
defenses when the planes were fired upon by Iraqi surface-to-air
missiles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
