<HEADLINE> New Conservation Area Established in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 30 (Xinhua) -- In the efforts to protect
its rich wildlife species, Nepal has established one more
conservation area covering the northern belt of Gorkha district in
the western part of the country, the official RSS news agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The mountainous Manaslu Conservation Area, which covers an area
of 1,663 square kilometers, has 200 species of plants, 19 types of
forests, 18 species of mammals and 20 species of birds, RSS said,
quoting a preliminary study.
</P>
<P>
Now the Himalayan kingdom has set up four conservation areas,
eight national parks, four wildlife reserves and one hunting
reserve since the conservation work started in 1972.
</P>
<P>
The country boasts, among others, 5,160 species of flowering
plants including 246 endemic ones, 687 species of algae and 465
lichen species.
</P>
<P>
It has 176 species of mammals, 43 species of amphibians, 100
species of reptiles, 844 species of birds, 180 species of fish and
635 species of butterflies, a conservation official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
