<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Trade Union Calls for Reduction of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 30 (Xinhua) -- President of the Zimbabwe
Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) Gibson Sibanda said Wednesday
that the size of country's cabinet must be reduced and the
government should control runaway inflation currently pegged at
45.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to have a big cabinet with all the luxuries
while the nation starves to death with more than 50 percent of
the population out of employment," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
According to Sibanda, the deepening economic crisis
Zimbabweans went through in 1998 was a time bomb despite the
government allegations that the ZCTU had a political agenda.
</P>
<P>
"Trade unions do not merely represent workers, they are a
major representative of civil society and as such they have a
special responsibility," Sibanda noted.
</P>
<P>
He said hard choices had to be made to create a better future
for the country.
</P>
<P>
"Through a social contract agreement, all social partners can
put their heads together beyond their traditional interests for
the survival of our nation," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
