<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Civil Servants Reject 25 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARATE, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean Goverment Staff
Association wednesday rejected the 25-percent salary increase
which the government awarded to civil servants last monday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the association Leonard Nkala told the Zimbabwe
News Agency that there was no way civil servants could accept the
25-percent increase because a consensus was not reached during
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Wage talks between the government and the association for a
salary increment broke down on wednesday last week after a
government negotiator said the state had no money to offer a
higher increase.
</P>
<P>
"If our employer does not review our situation, then we would
have no choice but to take drastic action as a way of pursuing
our grievances and that would be early next year," Nkala said.
</P>
<P>
He said civil servants would not be deterred by the
Presidential Temporary Measures Act which amended the Labor
Relations Act to make strikes illegal.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared for anything because that is a matter of life
and death and after all there has never been a legal strike in
this country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nkala's statement was in support of Public Service Association
executive secretary Charles Chiviru who wednesday said civil
servants still demanded a 20-percent cost of living adjustment in
addition to the 25-percent salary increase they were awarded by
the government on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
