</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Does Not Bow to Turkish Pressure: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot government spokesman
Christos Stylianides said Wednesday that Cyprus' decision to
cancel missile deployment was not bowing to Turkey's pressure.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem's
statement that Cyprus' decision was a result of pressure from
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Rather, he said the deployment of S-300 missiles on Greece's
Crete island is in line with the 1993 Cypriot-Greek defense pact.
under which Greece, the close ally of Greek Cypriot-dominated
government, will provide military assistance to Cyprus if it is
attacked.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides also said Cypriot government believes the decision
offers the opportunity for a smooth European Union (EU) accession
course kicked off last March.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides announced Tuesday night that
he has decided not to deploy the missiles in Cyprus and will
negotiate with Moscow to ship them to Greece's Crete island.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after his talks with Greek Prime Minister
Costas Simitis and a three-hour session of the National Council,
the top advisory body to the president on the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus ordered the surface-to-air missiles in January 1997 in a
bid to cement its air defense capability.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, the close ally of the independence-seeking Turkish
Cypriots in northern Cyprus, has threatened to launch a preemptive
strike on the missiles if they are deployed in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The U.N., the U.S. and Britain all have expressed opposition to
the missile deployment, which they said will increase tensions on
the east Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government has said that if there is substantive
progress toward a settlement to the Cyprus problem or if talks for
reduction of tensions and disarmament begins, leading to
demilitarization on the island, the deployment can be canceled.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island, in the
wake of a abortive pro-Greece coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-communal federation formula. But the peace talks have
been stalled since last year.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said that even though the preconditions were not
met to the full, the decision was taken in view of today's
international situation and to the benefit of Hellenism.
</P>
<P>
He added that the decision "also offers the international
community the opportunity to decide to tackle Turkish
provocations and intransigence in a substantive way that would
bring results."
</P>
<P>
Last week the U.N. Security Council adopted two resolutions
urging Secretary-General Kofi Annan to step up mediation efforts
between Greek and Turkish Cypriots and to secure a "staged
process" of reduction of troops and armaments in Cyprus. 
</P>
