<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Claims to Have Shot down Enemy Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 30 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi military spokesman
announced on Wednesday that Iraqi air-defense force has shot down
an enemy warplane flying over southern Iraq's no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 9:00 a.m. local time (0600 GMT),
formations of enemy warplanes approached Iraqi air-defense
positions in the southern no-fly zone, then Iraqi air-defense
force fired surface-to-air missiles and forced those planes to
flee.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was quoted by the Iraqi News Agency as saying
that Iraqi air-defense force was "almost certain" that they have
downed an enemy plane.
</P>
<P>
He said another formation of enemy planes then came and fired
missiles at a farm village, leading to the death of a farmer and
injury of another two.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi statement came almost eight hours after the incident
happened. Western military sources said an Iraqi air-defense site
in Talil in southern Iraq fired surface-to-air missiles at British
Tornado planes and was retaliated by U.S. F-16s with HARM missiles
and several 500-pound (225-kilogram) precision-guided bombs.
</P>
<P>
The sources said all U.S. and British warplanes patrolling the
northern no-fly zone returned safely to their base, again
contradicting the Iraqi claim.
</P>
<P>
This conflict was the second such in a week. In the previous
case on Monday, the Iraqis also said they shot down an enemy plane
that violated its air space in the northern no-fly zone, but
failed to produce evidence. The U.S. and Britain, however, said
they did not lose any jets in the clash.
</P>
<P>
The northern and southern no-fly zones in Iraq were imposed by
the U.S. and its allies in 1991 and 1992 respectively, with
claimed aims of protecting Kurds and Shiite Muslims from troops of
President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan has declared that his
government does not recognize the no-fly zones, set up "illegally"
by the U.S. and its allies without U.N. authorization, and
demanded that the U.N. discuss this issue.
</P>
<P>
"We are operating normally" in these zones, said Ramadan,
meaning Iraqi planes will defy the fly ban and challenge the
U.S. in the areas.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British forces gathering in the Gulf carried out four
consecutive nights of air strikes against Iraq December 16-19 to
punish Baghdad for not cooperating fully in U.N. weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
With their hope for an early lifting of crippling U.N.
sanctions dashed by the air raids, the Iraqis seemed to have
changed their tactics by barring the return of U.N. weapons
inspectors and challenging the U.S. in the no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
This threatens to turn U.S.-Iraq confrontation into a daily
occurrence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
