<HEADLINE> Iraq Urged to Apology for Invasion of Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the Arab
League Esmat Abdel-Meguid suggested Wednesday that the Iraqi
crisis might have been resolved if Iraq had apologized for its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The latest developments of the Iraqi crisis are "part of a long
chain of events that started with Iraq's invasion of Kuwait,"
Abdel-Meguid said in an Egyptian television talk show.
</P>
<P>
"This crisis could have been solved if the Iraqi regime
officially apologized for its aggression on a sisterly state," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid did not elaborate, but he appeared to be implying
that a formal Iraqi apology might convince Kuwait and its Gulf
allies to take reconciliatory steps.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League chief expressed regret over the postponement of
an Arab foreign ministers meeting to discuss a proposal for an
Arab summit on the Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting has been put off to January 24 at the
request of Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and other Gulf countries. Kuwait
and Saudi Arabia have not forgiven Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
for the invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which led the multinational forces in the
1991 Gulf War to oust Iraqi troops out of Kuwait, launched a
four-day missile attack against Iraq on December 16-19 in what
Washington called a retaliation to Baghdad's defiance of the
United Nations arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
U.N. arms inspectors have been overseeing the elimination of
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction since the end of the Gulf War.
They must certify that Iraq has destroyed all its banned weapons
before the U.N. Security Council lifts the sanctions imposed
on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
