<HEADLINE> Swaziland Turning to Total Dictatorship: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Banned parties in
Swaziland have warned that the country is turning into a total
dictatorship because of a new administration order.
</P>
<P>
Legislation, signed last week by Swazi King Mswati III, aimed
to give chiefs power to arrest and try people in their areas,
Southern African Broadcasting Association quoted Swazi opposition
sources as reporting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mario Masuku of the People's United Democratic Movement said
that his party believed the law was made to suppress the poor.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the law also gave traditional leaders
authority to evict from their land any citizen who did not comply
with the rules. It also enabled chiefs to act as attorneys,
judges and police officers.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Swaziland Federation of Trade Unions
Jan Sithole said the new law was a crime and an abuse of human
rights, noting that it would encourage confrontation between the
government and the people.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland, a traditional monarchy with less than one million
population, is the only country in Southern Africa which has not
introduced multi-party politics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
