<HEADLINE> Annan Dismayed by Angolan Failure to Cooperate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said on Wednesday that he is "deeply dismayed by the
continuing failure of the Government of Angola and UNITA to
provide access for a search-and-rescue team to the site of the
crash of a United Nations plane on Saturday."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here by his spokesman, Annan said,
"There can be no justification for not facilitating full and
immediate access to the crash site.
</P>
<P>
"United Nations staff have long risked -- and sacrificed --
their lives in their efforts to bring peace to Angola," the
statement said, "The Secretary-General expects the responsible
leaders to honor those efforts by guaranteeing the safety and
security of all United Nations staff" in the African Country.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General therefore reiterates his appeal to the
Angolan Government and UNITA to extend all possible assistance
to enable the United Nations Observer Mission in Angola (MOUNA)
to reach the crash site and to assist in search and rescue
operations for any survivors," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came one day after a presidential statement of
the Security Council, which on Tuesday urgently called on the
Angolan Government and the rebel UNITA to "cooperate immediately
and fully" with U.N. peacekeepers in search and rescue of 14
people aboard a U.N.-chartered cargo plane that crashed near war
zone in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, a MONUA statement, issued in the Angolan
capital of Luanda, said, "There could be survivors" aboard the
plane, which went missing on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The special representative of the U.N. Secretary-General in
Angola, Issa Diallo, "appeals in the strongest terms" to the
Angolan Government and UNITA to stop fighting around the crash
site, so that U.N. peacekeepers can visit the site of the accident
and try to save lives of the 14 persons, including four crew
members.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Government and the rebel UNITA, the National Union
for Total Independence of Angola, are currently locked in a fierce
fighting in the central highland area of the country, the crash
site of the U.N.-chartered cargo plane.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Spokesman's Office Tuesday disclosed a list of
nationalities of the missing passengers and crew members.
Passengers included three Angolans, an Australian, two Russians, a
Cameroonian, an Egyptian, a Namibian and a Zambian. The crew was
made up of an Angolan, a Bolivian, a Filipino and a South African.
</P>
<P>
The C-130 aircraft crashed 10 minutes after takeoff near the
central highland city Huambo, about 480 kilometers southeast of
Luanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
