<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Police Urged to Speed up Probe of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The defense side in the
U.S. embassy bombing case Wednesday urged Tanzanian police
authorities to complete investigations of the two suspects as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The defense advocate, Abdul Mwangera, told the Dar es
Salaam-based Kisutu Resident Magistrate's Court that he has grown
tired of endless investigations without giving reasons.
</P>
<P>
Mwangera also requested the Federal Bureau of Investigations
(FBI) and local police to hand back the clothes of the suspects
which were taken away for investigations, saying that such kind
of acts are unfair, illegal and against human rights.
</P>
<P>
He urged the police to adopt modern ways of investigation
rather than using the shirts of his clients.
</P>
<P>
On the prosecution side, Senior Superintendent of Police
Reinhard Lisapita, insisted that the clothes being held by the
police is one way of conducting investigations as the case is
serious.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of United States embassy in Dar es Salaam on
August 7 this year killed 11 people and injured more than 70
others. The suspects in the case are Mustafa Mahmoud Said Ahmed,
an Egyptian national, and Rashid Saleh Hemed, a Tanzanian. Both
are charged with murdering 11 persons.
</P>
<P>
The presiding magistrate, Principal Resident Magistrate
Projestus Lugazia, urged the prosecution side to disclose how far
they have gone in investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
The case is expected to come up for another mention on January
15 as the investigations are still incomplete. 
</P>
