<HEADLINE> Ramadan Slams Continued U.S., Britain Aggression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha
Yassin Ramadan on Wednesday accused the U.S. and Britain of
"still continuing their aggression against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egyptian and the United Arab Emirates TV,
Ramadan said the U.S. and Britain continued violating Iraqi air
space and launched missiles at Iraqi targets.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Iraqi News Agency, Ramadan said he
would not rule out a new aggression by Washington and London
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was bombarded for four consecutive nights On December
16-19 by the U.S. and Britain in "Operation Desert Fox," which
killed at least 25 people and wounded more than 70 others.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan said the mission of the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) overseeing Iraq's disarmament and its chairman Richard
Butler was over, for they "served the scheme of the U.S.-British
aggression against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Ramadan said Iraq reserves the right to demand compensation for
human and property damages caused by U.S.-British air strikes,
adding that Iraq would submit relevant documents for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Iraq does not recognize the two no-fly
zones set up in the north and south of the country, saying they
were imposed on Iraq unilaterally by the U.S. and Britain and
without authorization from the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The vice president pointed out that the violations of Iraqi air
space by the U.S. and Britain "is a direct encroachment of Iraq's
sovereignty and territorial integrity," saying Iraq would be
firmly against and resist this encroachment.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, an Iraqi military spokesman announced that
enemy planes violated the country's air space in the south and
fired missiles at a village, killing one farmer and injuring two
others.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Iraq air-defense force fired surface-to-air
missiles at the planes and were "almost certain" that an enemy
plane was shot down.
</P>
<P>
Western military sources said two British Tornado fighter jets
patrolling the southern no-fly zone, which stretches from the 33rd
parallel to the Gulf, was targeted by Iraqi air-defense radar and
fired at with six to eight surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
American F-16 fighters retaliated with HARM missiles and bombs
that hit the Iraqi air-defense site. All U.S. and British
warplanes reportedly returned safely to their base. 
</P>
