<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Govt Announces Textile Quota Management Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
announced Thursday the Textile Quota Management Policy for the new
year aimed at increasing export income.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here Thursday evening, Finance
Minister Ishaq Dar said the policy is aimed at full utilization of
the quota, value addition, and it will have a positive impact in
increasing exports by about 400 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said that after detailed meetings with textile associations,
it has been decided to allow 100 percent allocation of quota on
the basis of quantity exported by each exporter.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the exporters fetching higher value during
this year will be compensated from the quota available with the
government, said Dar.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the new policy will ensure maximum
unionization of textile quota as 90 percent will be allocated from
January 1, 1999, enabling the exporters to plan their exports well
in advance. Previously, 60 to 65 percent quota was allocated.
</P>
<P>
The First-come First-Served procedure for allocation of quota
has been further simplified as exporter can get it after making
shipment as well as advance reservation against bank guarantee, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The exporters will be allowed to use flexibilities available
under different bilateral agreements in January each year, he
said, adding that this will help exporters to plan their export
commitments well in advance.
</P>
<P>
Other features of the policy include strengthening of role of
private sector in textile quota management, expansion of Quota
Supervisory Council and entrusting of responsibility of
allocation, authentication of textile quota to textile
associations.
</P>
<P>
The minister hoped that the new policy will facilitate growth
of the weaker segments of the textile sector and will generate
more employment and investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
