<HEADLINE> Sick Elephant in Henan Has Healthy New Year's Eve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, December 31 (Xinhua) -- With best wishes from zoo
employees and local residents, Luweng, an aged female elephant in
the zoo of this capital of Henan Province, today observed the last
day of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Watching Luweng grab a piece of holiday cake with her trunk,
the people around cheered for her health after she had been fed
with an infusion of medicine and nutrients for 12 days, and
Luweng's keeper burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
Still lying on the ground, Luweng looked calm and peaceful, but
had little appetite for the many delicious foods in front of her,
including watermelon and sugarcane, her favorites.
</P>
<P>
Babu, Luweng's mate, had been moved to a neighboring
elephant-shed and watched lovingly, touching and attempting to
help Luweng stand up with his trunk. But Luweng was in a bad
temper and frightened Babu away with a sudden roar.
</P>
<P>
Luweng has been suffering from pancreatitis and other
complications since December 20, and has struggled to survive with
her strong will to live and and the great concern of the people
around her. She has been receiving infusions of 50,000 milliliters
of medicine a day since she became ill, said one zoologist.
</P>
<P>
To aid her recovery, Luweng, who has lived at the zoo for 12
years, will be taking large doses of traditional Chinese medicine
beginning today, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
