<HEADLINE> Zambia's Monthly Inflation Rate Up By 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's monthly inflation
rate for December has been recorded at 5.6 percent as compared
with November, representing an increase of 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zambia News Agency ZANA Thursday quoted David Diangamo,
director of census and statistics, as saying that the level of
inflation observed in December was mainly due to continued price
increases in food items such as 25-kilogram bag of mealie meal
which has risen from 17,632 to 18,769 Kwacha (one U.S. Dollars
equals 2,500 Kwacha).
</P>
<P>
Prices for other items including fuel, charcoal, electricity
charges and clothing had also gone up, said Diangamo.
</P>
<P>
A 20-liter tin of maize grain which was selling at 7,225
Kwacha last month is now selling at 8,589 Kwacha, reflecting an
increase of 19 percent, according to Diangamo.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that the year-on-year inflation rate for the
composite group stood at 30.6 percent for December compared with
26.1 percent for November.
</P>
<P>
For the metropolitan low and high income groups, the
year-on-year inflation rate was recorded at 31.1 and 30 percent
respectively and for the non-metropolitan group, it stood at 30.7
percent, said the official. 
</P>
