<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qinghai Produces Over Two Million Tons of Oil, Gas in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The output of oil and gas at
the Qinghai oil field in northwest China hit a record two million
tons in 1998, according to figures released by the Qinghai
Petroleum Bureau today.
</P>
<P>
Located in the Qaidam Basin of the northern Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, the Qinghai oil field has so far produced 15.5 million
tons of crude oil and 2.1 billion square meters of gas since
exploration began there in 1954.
</P>
<P>
Qinghai Petroleum Bureau officials attribute the output growth
to new oil extraction technologies, and said crude oil output
increased to 5,170 tons a day in 1998, compared to 4,500 tons by
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, three gas pipes were installed in the field, and the
1998 gas output of 262 million square meters laid a solid basis
for the total output of oil and gas of over two million tons, said
the officials.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that the oil and natural gas reserves in the
Qinghai oil field will be found to be 600 million tons (1,000
square meters of natural gas equals one ton of crude oil) by the
end of this century, with an annual oil and gas output of three
million tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
