<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Feature: Monetary Union Finally A Reality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Yet another welcome
changeover in Europe: sure.
</P>
<P>
But it is poles apart in scale and significance from such
previous ones as the change from old French franc to the new and
from Britain's old pounds, shillings and pence to decimal
currency.
</P>
<P>
The New Year will usher in the biggest transfer of financial
sovereignty in history with the establishment of a single
currency for 290 million people in 11 countries.
</P>
<P>
The change affects not merely these 11 countries. Any country
in the world that has financial links with the countries that are
scheduled to use the common monetary system known as the euro
will feel the impact.
</P>
<P>
Hailed as the keystone of European integration, the single
currency was finally born after years of hectic preparation, both
by the countries participating and by the institutions that
administer the welfare of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the euro, though officially the final phase of
the economic and monetary union, is seen rather as the start of a
far-reaching and profound undertaking that got underway four
decades ago in the form of a common market on the European
continent.
</P>
<P>
The bloc has transformed itself from a six-nation group into a
15-nation league that now has 12 more countries applying for
membership.
</P>
<P>
Unlike Jean Monnet, the founding father of the European Union,
the integration engineers in his wake now have to take into
account the internal and external adaptation so as to make their
union capable of accommodating 27 and maybe even more countries,
not to mention dealing with an assortment of problems.
</P>
<P>
Barely will the launch of euro have passed than the European
Union will face up to at least three problems pinpointed in its
reform program, Agenda 2000.
</P>
<P>
The interlocked problems are enlargement, an improved common
agricultural policy and a tighter budget for the period from 2000
to 2006.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government from the 15 member states
failed to redress any of these problems during their Vienna
summit two weeks ago and only agreed to deal with them in a
special summit next March.
</P>
<P>
The euro will thus have to brace itself against the pressure
and trials from both within and outside the union, and all the 11
participating countries in the single currency will have to
practise austerity so as to help make the euro a success.
</P>
<P>
To avoid failure, euro zone governments, no longer having to
juggle with exchange rates to render their countries' goods and
services competitive, will have to become more efficient and have
to cooperate in taxation and social policy to deal with
persistent problems such as unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Though the structural reform of the European Union has lagged
somewhat behind schedule, the launch of the monetary union went
ahead exactly in accordance with planning. European Commission
President Jacques Santer said that the launch of euro was not
just economic. It was of great importance to the envisaged
political integration, he added.
</P>
<P>
Though the European Union countries of Britain, Denmark and
Sweden are staying out of the monetary union by choice, while
Greece failed to qualify, the combined efforts of Germany,
France, Italy, the Netherlands, Luxembourg, Belgium, Spain,
Portugal, Ireland, Finland and Austria, must turn the euro into
the anticipated keystone of a process many have striven to
achieve by means of both force and peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
