<HEADLINE> 123 People Killed in South Lebanon in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A total of 123 Lebanese and
Israelis were killed in conflicts in south Lebanon in 1998, the
Orient radio reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of those killed, 24 were Israeli soldiers, 34 militiamen from
the Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army, 42 Lebanese anti-Israeli
guerrillas and 23 Lebanese civilians, the radio quoted security
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that over 200 others were wounded in south
Lebanon, where Israel carved out a self-declared security zone in
1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has since been
spearheading a guerrilla war against Israel's occupation.
</P>
<P>
It launched a total of 1,300 attacks on Israeli posts inside
the zone with heavy machine guns, grenades and remote-controlled
bombs in the outgoing year.
</P>
<P>
In return, Israeli warplanes made 116 raids on Hezbollah's
targets across Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Though the death toll of Israeli soldiers in south Lebanon
dropped this year compared with last year's 39, calls in Israel for
a withdrawal from Lebanon are mounting.
</P>
<P>
However, the Israeli government has to date insisted that any
withdrawal from Lebanon follow a negotiated security agreement
with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the Israeli demand, asking it to leave the
country without any condition, as stipulated in the
U.N. Resolution 425. 
</P>
</TEXT>
