<HEADLINE> Pak Central Bank Calls for Promotion of Self-Reliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The State Bank of Pakistan
(SBP) has underscored the need for promoting self-reliance by
encouraging national savings and promoting consumption austerity
so that Pakistan can live within its means.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report for 1997-98 released Thursday, the SBP
said Pakistan's balance of payments has been vulnerable for quite
some time as large current account deficit has been financed
largely through debt creating short-term inflows which caused
foreign debt burden.
</P>
<P>
It called for direct foreign investment and medium-term debt
instruments to meet balance of payments. The Bank said that to
achieve medium-term goals, the government must broaden the tax
base.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank said the nuclear explosion conducted by
Pakistan in May this year and subsequent sanctions had large
fallout effects on the economy.
</P>
<P>
It affected the investors' confidence, the external sector came
under great pressure and during the first five months
(July-November) of the current fiscal year, the exports declined
by 12.4 percent, heavy borrowing by the government caused pressure
on fiscal position of the government, tax collection fell short of
the target while corporations failed to fully meet debt service
obligation.
</P>
<P>
According to the report the home remittances by overseas
Pakistanis declined by 39 percent and foreign investment by
two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
The external sector came under great pressure. During the first
five months (July-November) of the current fiscal year, exports
declined by 12.4 percent and imports by 20.1 percent over the
corresponding period last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
These declines have obvious implications both for the
government revenue and the tempo of economic activity in the
country.
</P>
<P>
However, despite these developments, the balance of payments on
current account (excluding resident foreign currency deposits)
from July to November showed improvement compared with the same
period last year, largely because of decline in imports.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of the trends so far, current account balance for
the year is likely to decline from 3.2 percent of the GDP during
1997-98 to three percent in the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Central Bank said that total national debt at
the end of June this year had reached 2,518 billion rupees (54.7
billion U.S. dollars) or 91.2 percent of the GDP. Serving of the
debt has become a major national problem.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank said the size of the debt needs to be
contained to manageable limits through various policy measures,
including debt retirement through the use of privatization
proceeds and sale of government property, and by offering shares
of public sector enterprises to holders of debt.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, dependence on foreign debt should be reduced by
encouraging inflow of direct foreign investment and substituting
short-term loans with medium-term debt instruments, the Bank said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
