<HEADLINE> Pak Economy to Recover in Next 6 Months: SBP Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The State Bank of Pakistan
(SBP) has forecast that Pakistan's economy will recover
substantially in the second half (January-June) of the current
fiscal year from the adverse developments since May this year.
</P>
<P>
The SBP said in its annual report for 1997-98 issued Thursday
the agriculture sector is expected to achieve a growth rate of
five percent, industrial revival in the second half of the year is
expected to push up the overall growth of the industrial sector
close to that of last year.
</P>
<P>
The annual rate of inflation is expected to remain in a single
digit and deficit in the current account of the balance of
payments is expected to decline from 3.2 percent of the Gross
Domestic Product in 1997-98 to three percent in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
All external payments are expected to be regularized soon, and
foreign exchange reserves are projected to increase to the range
of 1.4 billion U.S. dollars to 2 billion dollars by the end of the
current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The SBP said that by the end of June 1999, conditions of
normalcy must be re-established, investors' confidence should come
back and conditions could begin to be restored for stabilization
and resumption of high growth.
</P>
<P>
However, the Central Bank report said, the restoration of
confidence and achievement of growth and stability would require
careful handling of the economy on a sustained basis.
</P>
<P>
Relief in external debt payments and resumption of resource
inflows from international financial institutions would provide a
breathing space for the restructuring of the economy so as to
achieve self-reliance and reduce the need for large external
assistance or debt on a continuous basis. 
</P>
