<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: HK's External Economic Ties Expanding After Handover (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The economic and trade
relations between Hong Kong and the rest of the world have been
further strengthened and developed after it became a special
administrative region (SAR) of China on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Before the handover, some people worried that Hong Kong's
external relations would contract after its return to China, but
facts have proved that Hong Kong's external relations have enjoyed
an obvious expansion after July 1, 1997, said Michael Suen,
secretary for constitutional affairs of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
Just as many SAR government officials and Hong Kong businessmen
have said, because Hong Kong is a small-sized economy and lacks
natural resources, external economic and trade relations are vital
for it to maintain its status as an international trade, financial
and shipping center.
</P>
<P>
The smooth and continuous development of Hong Kong's external
economic relations is based on the concept of "one country, two
systems" and guaranteed by the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, Hong Kong remains a separate
Customs territory, has no foreign exchange control, continues the
free market economic principle, and maintains a free port.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law also stipulates that representatives of the HKSAR
government may participate in international conferences as members
of the Chinese government delegations and the HKSAR may, on its
own, using the name "Hong Kong, China," maintain and develop
relations and conclude and implement agreements with foreign
states and regions and relevant international organizations.
</P>
<P>
After the handover, Hong Kong, in the name of "Hong Kong,
China," maintains its full membership in the World Trade
Organization, of which China as a whole is still not a member, and
in the Asia-Pacific Economic Conference (APEC), of which China is
also a member.
</P>
<P>
During the conferences that Hong Kong representatives
participated in, either as members of the Chinese government
delegations or on their own in the name of "Hong Kong, China,"
they may express their own views on behalf of and in the interest
of the Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
In some conferences, for example the APEC, HKSAR
representatives may even express views different from that of the
Central government of China.
</P>
<P>
During the past 18 months, the SAR has signed more than 20
bilateral agreements with foreign countries in various areas
including mutual legal assistance, air services, air transit and
investment promotion and protection. Nearly 80 more agreements are
being negotiated.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the agreements has provided convenience for the
expansion of ties between Hong Kong and these countries in the
fields of economy, trade and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Under the accords for the promotion and protection of investors
concluded with 15 countries, Hong Kong and these countries agreed
to mutually provide for equal treatment of investors and for the
settlement of investment disputes in accordance with international
norms.
</P>
<P>
Through these agreements, the interests of investors are fully
guaranteed and Hong Kong's position as a financial and trade
center has been strengthened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: HK's External Economic Ties Expanding After Handover (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The overseas visits by Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa and other
senior government officials to dozens of countries and regions
around the world have played an important role in expanding Hong
Kong's external economic ties.
</P>
<P>
One of the tasks of Tung's overseas trips is to persuade these
countries and regions to grant visa-free access to HKSAR passport
holders.
</P>
<P>
Now 56 countries and regions have agreed to grant visa-free
access to HKSAR passport holders, bringing convenience to Hong
Kong businessmen to do business or to invest in these countries
and regions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hong Kong has granted visa-free access to passport
holders of 170 countries and regions. The move has helped attract
foreign businessmen and tourists to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Almost each of the overseas visits was accompanied by a group
of Hong Kong businessmen, and issues about economic and trade
cooperation between Hong Kong and these countries were listed
on their agenda.
</P>
<P>
During Tung's visit to the European Union in October 1997, a
new business forum, the Hong Kong/EU--EU/Hong Kong Business
Cooperation Committees were set up.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang made a three-week mission to
Europe and the United States in September this year to exchange
views with the world's financial leaders on the restoration of
order and stability in the international financial market.
</P>
<P>
During his trip, Tsang explained the rationale behind the SAR
government's counter measures against the manipulators in Hong
Kong's stock and futures markets and convinced the world financial
leaders that Hong Kong is still pursuing the free market policy.
</P>
<P>
Administrative Secretary Anson Chan and Chief Executive of the
Hong Kong Monetary Authority Joseph Yam had participated in the
exhibitions organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council
(TDC) in New York and Tokyo to promote Hong Kong's financial
services.
</P>
<P>
While senior officials went out to promote Hong Kong around the
world, heads of state and government of many foreign countries
have come to Hong Kong, usually on the last leg of their visits to
China.
</P>
<P>
Among the distinguished visitors were presidents of the United
States, Bulgaria, the Philippines and South Korea, the King of
Norway, vice president of South Africa, prime ministers of Britain
and France and many other foreign dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
These high-level exchanges of visits have helped strengthen and
develop the economic and trade relations between Hong Kong and
these countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
