<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: HK's External Economic Ties Expanding After Handover (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong has also hosted a series of large scale international
conferences after its return to China.
</P>
<P>
Conferences held in Hong Kong in 1997 included the annual
meetings of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World
Bank (WB), the International Investment Funds Conference, the 57th
Ministerial Meeting of the Group of 24 Developing Countries, the
World Economic Forum's Sixth East Asia Economic Summit, and the
28th General Assembly of the World Trade Centers Association.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 Hong Kong hosted the Ninth Annual International
Corporate Conference of the Asia Society and the Asian Regional
Symposium '98 of the World Intellectual Property Organization.
Various medium and small-scale international conferences and
exhibitions had never stopped in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Even after the Asian financial turmoil struck Hong Kong in
October 1997, Hong Kong's status as a city of international
business is still there.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, over 25,000 foreign companies have set up their
regional headquarters or offices in Hong Kong and most of them are
optimistic about the long-term prospect of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Trade Development Council has conducted nearly
400 business and trade promoting activities (including
exhibitions, business conferences and seminars) in over 40
countries and regions around the world in the past one and a half
years.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 trade delegations from all over the world
(excluding China's mainland) have paid visits to Hong Kong in the
past two years. The number of trade delegations from the mainland
has added up to 282.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Monetary Authority has kept and developed close
relations with central banks of other countries and regions and
international organizations such as the IMF, WB and the Asian
Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
In July this year, the Bank of International Settlement (BIS)
set up a representative office in Hong Kong. It is the first
overseas office for the BIS, headquartered in Basal, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
With the support from the central government of China, Hong
Kong had beaten its rivals -- Japan and Singapore -- to win the
trust of the BIS by its business-friendly environment.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the office of the BIS in Hong Kong reinforces
the status of Hong Kong as a leading international financial
center and has demonstrated that the international financial
community had cast a vote of confidence in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
