<HEADLINE> Williams, White honored "Gongs" in Britain New Years List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Frank Williams, owner of the
Formula One team that bears his name, and snooker's most popular
player, Jimmy White, were honored on Thursday in Britain's
traditional New Year's List.
</P>
<P>
Williams received a knighthood, the highest honor awarded to
the nine people associated with sport on the list, meaning he
should now be addressed as Sir Frank.
</P>
<P>
"I am surprised and very happy that I received such an
important honor," he said in a statement. "Additionally, I am
truly delighted that the team's achievements in grand prix racing
have been recognized in this way."
</P>
<P>
Williams formed Williams Grand Prix Engineering in 1977 and
the team have since won seven formula one titles.
</P>
<P>
White, nicknamed Whirlwind for his fast, almost insouciant
style of snooker, was awarded an MBE (Member of the British
Empire), the lowest rung on the "gongs" ladder, along with
heptathlete Denise Lewis, boxer "Prince" Naseem Hamed, cricketer
Angus Fraser and soccer player Stuart Pearce.
</P>
<P>
"I've had a bit of a year," said White, whose son Tommy Tiger
was born recently. White, who has lost six Embassy world finals,
said he planned to play on for another five years in an attempt
to win the elusive championship.
</P>
<P>
The honors list is prepared by Prime Minister Tony Blair but
ordinary Britons are encouraged to propose names for inclusion.
</P>
</TEXT>
