<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: 1998: Bangladesh in Retrospect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The year 1998 ends in Bangladesh
with unprecedented havoc created by the century's worst flood and
events which have either made people depressed or brought them new
hopes.
</P>
<P>
The beginning of the year saw the start of surrender of the
tribal insurgents in the southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts
following the signing of a government-rebel peace treaty in
December 1997, and the completion of the return to the hill region
of nearly 60,000 tribal refugees from the bordering Indian state
of Tripura.
</P>
<P>
An atmosphere of peace is prevailing in the hill tracts after
more than two decades of armed struggle in which thousands lost
their lives.
</P>
<P>
The year was marked by a devastating flood between July and
September, which lasted more than 11 weeks inundating two-thirds
of the country and affected one-third of the total population
claiming over 1,100 lives.
</P>
<P>
The flood caused enormous losses of property and human lives,
and mental sufferings to the Bangladeshi people, whose hopes of
eradicating poverty and achieving prosperity would have to remain
dreams for years to come.
</P>
<P>
In the political arena, the return to parliament of the
opposition law-makers in March gave many people the hope of a
political reconciliation, but their hopes were smashed when the
opposition launched in June a "long march" movement toward the
hill region "to safeguard the country's independence and
sovereignty," and to press their demand for the scrap of the peace
treaty which it accused of "violating the Constitution" and
"ignoring the interests of the nation."
</P>
<P>
Hopes of political stability in the country revived when the
ruling Bangladesh Awami League decided in November to renounce
hartal "either in power or in opposition" following an
opposition-called three-day countrywide strike and the opposition
responded by listing conditions for an end to hartals.
</P>
<P>
The judgment in November of the killing case of former
president Sheikh Mujibur Rahman was one of the country's major
events of the year. The verdict, which "strengthened the
foundation of the rule of law in the country," came 23 years after
Mujibur Rahman, father of incumbent Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina,
was assassinated in a plot on August 15, 1975.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka successfully hosted the first business summit of
Bangladesh, India and Pakistan in January this year, and a
ministerial meeting of the BIMST-EC (Bangladesh-India-Myanmar-Sri
Lanka-Thailand Economic Cooperation forum) in December, playing a
significant role in strengthening regional cooperation,
particularly in the field of economic development.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh managed to resume the repatriation of some 21,000
Myanmar refugees staying in southeastern Cox's Bazar district in
November, and signed agreed-upon minutes with India the same month
on border-related issues, including the demarcation of a nearly
6.5-kilometer stretch of border which remained unfinished.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the positive signs and progress in 1998, there
exist problems unsolved, such as India's reportedly attempt to
push Bengali-speaking "Indian nationals" into Bangladesh, the slow
repatriation process of the Myanmar refugees, and more
importantly, a slow economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh scored an unprecedented 5.9 percent economic growth
during the last fiscal year ending on June 30, 1998 and set an
ambitious target of 6 percent for the current 1998-99 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The target was slimmed down to 4 percent following the
protracted deluge and a drop in export earnings, which registered
a 5-percent negative growth during the first four months of the
current fiscal year compared with that of the same period of the
previous year, and 14 percent short of the target.
</P>
<P>
The year 1998 also witnessed the successful hosting by
Bangladesh of the Wills International Cup Cricket Tournament in
late October and early November and the opening in June of the
950-million-dollar multi-purpose Jamuna Bridge, the longest bridge
in the country and in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
All these have brought excitement to the Bangladeshi people who
hope that the coming New Year would be a better year for them with
fast economic growth and a stable political situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebel Group Builds up Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF), the major rebel group in the Philippines, has built
up its forces to 11,990 guerrillas now from 8,200 two years ago, a
military report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Muslim rebel group has added 3,790
fighters to its forces in the past two years in the Southern
Philippines, mostly in Central Mindanao, where the MILF has
established its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the military report said, the MILF also
acquired additional fire power and has 8,240 assorted firearms
now, up by 1,275 from the 6,965 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The buildup of firepower and recruitment activities occurred
while a ceasefire agreement between the government and the MILF is
in place, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, it noted that gunbattles between the government and
the MILF had gone down from 369 in 1997 to 293 in 1998 because of
the existing truce.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the ceasefire, fatalities from both sides had
decreased drastically since 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The MILF has recently threatened to escalate the fighting if
the government would not accept its demand for an independent
state in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
But President Joseph Estrada rejected the demand last Monday,
saying that the demand of the MILF for an Islamic state in
Mindanao would be granted only "over my dead body."
</P>
<P>
The President warned that the government is prepared to "meet
violence with violence."
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between the government and the MILF have been going
 on since last year to find a peaceful and lasting solution to the
 long-drawn Mindanao problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
