<HEADLINE> Star Singer Lures Chinese Pop Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese pop music fans are
waiting excitedly for the arrival of American singer Richard Marx,
who will perform his first concerts in China in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
Chicago-born Marx has been at forefront of the pop music
business for many years and is one of the earliest western
singers introduced to Chinese music fans ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that he has the biggest Chinese fan club of any
European or American singer.
</P>
<P>
So, while New Year movies and Christmas sales might offer
attractions for many, the prospect of a Marx concert is a big
event for the young Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Already boys and girls are seeking tickets for the two shows on
January 15 and 16.
</P>
<P>
Subway stations in downtown Beijing and roadside billboards are
decorated with giant posters of the 35-year-old rock and roll
star. Song Jing, a woman in her twenties who is studying at
Beijing Broadcasting Institute for her master's degree, said, "I
can hardly wait to see Richard at his concert."
</P>
<P>
"But I don't know if I'll be lucky enough to get his
autograph," she added.
</P>
<P>
Richard Marx, a thundering good name for a pop star, recently
caused a new fad in the Chinese capital. His latest album Days
With Love has become a big hit with his fans who have besieged
Beijing's music stores for copies.
</P>
<P>
The Cultural Entertainment Company under China's Performance
Abroad Agency (CPAA), the shows' organizer, said that the concerts
have sold well even though the most expensive tickets are priced
at 500 yuan (60 U.S. dollars), the average monthly wage of a
worker here.
</P>
<P>
Marx, who likes wearing jeans, shot to worldwide fame with his
song Right Here Waiting, which took the highest position in the
U.S. Billboard's Top Ten for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
"I hope Richard will give us something exciting and bring a
real carnival here," said Wang Beibei, a Beijing music fan.
</P>
<P>
The twice Grammy Awards nominee also plans to perform in
Shanghai on January 20.  
</P>
</TEXT>
