<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tackles Pollution in Taihu Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese officials have vowed
to clean up the highly polluted Taihu Lake, China's third largest
freshwater late in the south, in the coming new year.
</P>
<P>
All factories in the area failing to meet new waste water
emission standards will be shut down tonight and there will be no
bargaining, according to Xie Zhenhua, director of the State
Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA).
</P>
<P>
The tough measures are expected to cut the area's industrial
water pollution by a large margin.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 85 percent of the major polluters each producing more
than 100 tons of waste water a day in the lake valley have
installed treatment facilities to clean up the water disposal.
Another 143 polluters have been closed down not acting fast enough
to tackle the pollution problem.
</P>
<P>
SEPA officials say that the anti-pollution campaign launched in
the area in 1998 has been quite successful. However, they pointed
out that the bulk of the waste water comes from urban sewage.
</P>
<P>
"To clean up the lake properly, urban sewage must be
controlled," they stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to a government plan to clean up Taihu Lake, 33 urban
sewage plants with a daily treatment capacity of more than 1.6
million tons of water would have been completed in the lake valley
by the end of 1998. However, only two have so far come into
operation, with 14 still under construction and another 17 still
in the planning stage.
</P>
<P>
"Lack of funds is the major problem," said a SEPA official, who
explained that although the central government has earmarked
certain funds for the projects, local governments and financial
organizations have not shown similar enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, from tomorrow discharging phosphoric detergents in
the lake will be banned. Shu Jinhua, a research fellow with the
Chinese Academy of Sciences said that the measure will cut
phosphoric emissions by 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zang Yuxiang, vice-director of SEPA's Pollution Control
Department, added that tonight's crackdown on industrial polluters
will cut phosphoric emission by a further 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
"If tough measures are taken against agricultural polluters, we
can reduce the pollution level by another 15 percent," he added.
</P>
<P>
The phosphoric materials in the lake are attributed to an
over-abundance of algae in the water, causing serious pollution
problems.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the state's clean up target can be achieved
only under the condition that phosphoric emissions are cut by 80
percent.
</P>
<P>
Chinese environmental expert Qian Yi said that China should be
fully prepared to engage in a protracted war with those polluting
the lake.
</P>
<P>
"Tonight's action is just a beginning," he warned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0085 </DOCNO>
