<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Adopts New Assistance Strategies for Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Under its new Country
Assistance Strategy (CAS) for Nepal, the World Bank will, in the
next three years, bring the resources closer to the beneficiaries
and support collective donor action to foster stronger governance
to reduce waste and mismanagement, the bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In coordination with Nepal's new Local Self-Governance Act, the
CAS which was approved on December 15 emphasizes district-level
project implementation and greater beneficiary participation in
project design, construction and maintenance, the bank said in a
press release.
</P>
<P>
"The CAS states that the abundance of foreign assistance to
Nepal, while achieving some successes, has also shielded Nepal
from underlying structural problems and has often substituted for
the creation of national capacity to plan and implement
development programs," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"It therefore calls for greater donor coordination with
emphasis on institutional development. Such cooperation is also
needed to improve governance," it added.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that in parallel with these efforts, the CAS
stresses the need to strengthen both private sector project
implementation and the central government's crucial responsibility
for monitoring and evaluating the projects.
</P>
<P>
On the broader development outlook for the country, the central
message of the CAS is that faster and sustainable growth, more
equitably distributed throughout the country, is needed to make
substantial progress in reducing poverty.
</P>
<P>
It also emphasizes the need for continued improvement in
national economic and fiscal management, especially strengthening
of the tax base, a better allocation and management of public
resources, reform of the financial sector and further
privatization.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, the World Bank held extensive public
consultations on the CAS in various locations throughout Nepal
from January through September this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
