<HEADLINE> Two Nigerian Parties Decide to Present Joint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The All People's Party (APP)
and the Alliance for Democracy (AD) have resolved to present a
joint presidential candidate for next year's general elections in
a bid to check the victory run of the People's Democratic Party
(PDP).
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued Tuesday at the end of a joint committee
meeting of the two parties, APP and AD said that they had agreed
to pick the presidential candidate from the southern part of the
country, This Day newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that both parties are committed to the
principle of restructuring with a view to returning Nigeria to
true federation.
</P>
<P>
The two parties resolved to cooperate electorally for the
promotion and sustenance of civil democracy as opposed to
"militarized democracy", beginning with the governorship and
state house of assembly elections on January 9.
</P>
<P>
So, the communique said, APP and AD would most likely ask
their supporters to vote for whichever of the two parties is
stronger in any of the 36 states in the west African country
during the January 9 elections.
</P>
<P>
Efforts made in the early days of the formation of political
parties in the country to bring them under one umbrella failed as
the AFENIFERE and the People's Consultative Forum politicians who
are now AD members vowed not to have anything to do with those
people they dubbed "Abacha politicians" in the APP.
</P>
<P>
But, after the local government elections held early this
month, it is clear to APP and AD parties that if they want to check
the winning streak of the PDP, they must sink their differences
and work together, said the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
