<HEADLINE> Cambodian Parliament Passes Fiscal 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian National
Assembly adopted Thursday the country's fiscal 1999 budget, with
no major changes in revenue and expenditure compared to last
year's budget.
</P>
<P>
The budget was adopted after a nearly two-day debate, with 98
votes in favor which reached the quorum.
</P>
<P>
The annual budget is about 420 million U.S. dollars, of which
almost half depends upon foreign aids and loan. At the same time,
half of its domestic revenue will come from import tax. The total
spending is just the same as the revenue, with no deficit.
</P>
<P>
The expenditure on military and security are still high
compared to previous years.
</P>
<P>
According to the budget, about 89 million dollars will be spent
on defense, which accounts about 40 percent of the total budget
and drops about 6 percent as compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
Keat Chhon, Minister of Finance and Economy, told the Assembly
Wednesday that "what we spent on defense and security is important
for the country. Although the war is finished we have to spend it
for buying peace and security."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the budget increased the spending on health by 47
percent, education by 13 percent and agriculture by 59 percent,
although those areas still make up only a small percentage of
overall spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
