<HEADLINE> Nepal Makes Encouraging Achievements in Tourism Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Nepali officials said here
Thursday that encouraging achievements have been made in the Visit
Nepal Year'98, the first of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a function called "See You Again - Grand Finale"
held at the end of the tourism year, Minister for Tourism and
Civil Aviation Bhim Bahadur Rawal said that throughout the year
various programs were organized across the country through the
broad-based coordination of the Nepalese people, the government
and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
"This national campaign has clearly established strong
commitment on the part of the people to the cause of tourism
development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Activities related to infrastructure development have been
carried out in the period, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Visit Nepal Year'98 campaign has increased awareness and
participation of the people in tourism and enhanced the image of
Nepal as a destination in the international market, besides
promoting domestic tourism," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
He held that the campaign has also contributed to the
development of quality in the Nepalese tourism to some extent.
"Quality tourism will be our focus of activity in 1999 and
beyond," he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that according to a World Tourism
Organization report, the year 1998 does not show encouraging
trends in the world tourism compared with the past years.
</P>
<P>
"Despite this odd, Nepal registered a positive growth in
tourist arrivals in 1998," he said. "This achievement is clearly
the contribution of Visit Nepal Year'98."
</P>
<P>
Nepal aims to attract 500,000 tourists this year, but by the
end of November, tourist arrivals by air stood at 360,875, up 11.8
percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is a major foreign exchange earner for the Himalayan
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Dipendra Purush Dhakal, secretary at the Ministry of Tourism
and Civil Aviation, also told the function that the image of Nepal
has been reestablished among the international community.
</P>
<P>
"Nepal is again being selected as one of the prime destinations
by tourists," he said. "Had this been not the case, four
international airlines -- Gulf, Transavia, Austrian and Condor --
would not have started their flights from Nepal in the same year."
</P>
<P>
Queen Aishwarya and Crown Prince Dipendra graced the function
attended by some 3,000 people.
</P>
<P>
An hour-long cultural and religious programs were presented on
the occasion by different castes of the Nepalese people. 
</P>
