<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> End of the Housing Nightmare for China's College Teachers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to remodel living
accommodation for more than 180,000 teachers living in rundown
housing the Chinese government has set up a special fund of 2.15
billion yuan (260 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
It has also set a deadline for the transformation work to be
completed by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that young college teachers and faculty members
working in education establishments nationwide, and under the
control of central government, are those facing the most
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
In 67 Beijing universities and colleges there are 164
poorly-equipped buildings waiting to be remodeled with a total
floor space of 480,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Like most young college teachers in Beijing, Xu Tao, a
32-year-old researcher at Peking University, lives with his wife
and their five-year-old son in a tiny room the size of four
ping-pong tables. It is crammed with a large bed, a table, a
heavily-stocked bookshelf, a small desk, a refrigerator and three
chairs.
</P>
<P>
China's top leadership told the presidents of the country's
major universities recently that such crude housing should not be
permitted in the next century.
</P>
<P>
These rundown buildings on college campuses were first built in
the 1950s as students' dormitories but later became homes for
teachers and staff due to the increasing numbers of faculty
members. The rooms are bird cage-like and cooking has to be done
in corridors. There are also limited toilet facilities which have
to be shared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> End of the Housing Nightmare for China's College Teachers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I became a researcher at Institute of Microelectronics in
Peking University this April and my project is quite
time-consuming," said Xu. "But I can find no quiet space to work
at night in my home. I want nothing more than two separate rooms
with our own kitchen and toilet," he added.
</P>
<P>
When Vice-Premier Li Lanqing announced his plans to solve the
issue no later than the end of the century, Xu and his wife were
overjoyed.
</P>
<P>
Xu revealed that one of his friends became so disillusioned
that he had made up his mind to go abroad and find a better
future. "He had asked the university to provide a room for his
parents but to no avail," explained Xu.
</P>
<P>
Although Peking University has built new housing for faculty
members, totalling more than 200,000 square meters, in the last 20
years the housing demands have also increased rapidly and are far
from being satisfactorily met.
</P>
<P>
A shortage of funds and a decreasing availability of land are
the university's daunting problems, according to Tang Xingsheng,
who is in charge of the university's general affairs.
</P>
<P>
Tang explained that after working out a thorough, comprehensive
plan to tackle the issues, the university has decided to build new
off-campus apartments for its young teachers, instead of
modernizing the old buildings, which is only a temporary remedy.
</P>
<P>
After some senior faculty members have moved to new apartments,
their previous rooms can also become a part of the housing stock
and the university can live up to its promise of meeting the hopes
of its young staff.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
