<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Peace-makers Dominate UK's Honors List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- British former Prime Minister
John Major becomes a Companion of Honor on the New Year Honors
list for his vital work for peace in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Leading a list of almost 1,000 members of the British
society, ranging from parliamentarians to shepherds, Major was
picked out by his successor Tony Blair for his groundwork that
led the province to its historic Good Friday agreement in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's official spokesman said Blair had wanted
to honor those who had "helped give peace a chance" in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. Senator George Mitchell, chair of the Northern
Ireland peace talks, was awarded an honorary Knighthood. But as a
foreign citizen, he is not allowed to hold a full honor.
</P>
<P>
His co-chairman in the talks General Alfred John Gardyne
Drummond de Chastelain, a Canadian and therefore member of the
Commonwealth, was also named a Companion of Honor.
</P>
<P>
A doctor, a policeman and a council official who played vital
roles in the aftermath of the Omagh bombing, the worst atrocity
in Northern Ireland's troubled history, were also named on the
list.
</P>
<P>
More than half of those named on the list are recognized
specifically for their voluntary service, the highest yet
recorded on any list.
</P>
<P>
They are joined by a pantheon of names from the fields of
politics, entertainment, sport and business.
</P>
<P>
Five life peers are created, including Onora Sylvia O'Neill,
principal of Cambridge University's Newnham College and Sir Naren
Patel, consultant obstetrician and lately president of Royal
College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
