<HEADLINE> Nigeria May Adopt 1979 Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A special committee set up to
co-ordinate debate on the 1995 constitution has recommended the
adopting of the 1979 constitution with some amendents, press
reports said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the special committee's final report to the Head of
State, General Abdulsalami Abubakar Wednesday, the committee's
chairman Justice Niki Tobi said from the finding of the
committee, "it is clear that Nigerians basically opt for the 1979
constitution with relevant amendents."
</P>
<P>
The 1995 constitution was drafted by the former military
government of late General Sani Abacha but it was never
promulgated.
</P>
<P>
The most important and controversial provision of the 1995
constitution is the rotation of the presidency among the six
geopolitical zones, which is designed to break the monopoly of
the power by the north in most of the time since Nigeria's
independence in 1960.
</P>
<P>
To provide a constitutional base for the on-going transition
to civil rule program and the coming civilian government,
Abubakar who took the power in June following Abacha's sudden
death, inaugurated the Constitutional Debate Coordinating
Committee on November 11 to advise the government on the 1995
constitution before its promulgation.
</P>
<P>
The coordinating committee has received 405 memoranda on the
new constitution from Nigerians within and outside the country.
</P>
<P>
Based on the memoranda, Tobi said, the committee has
"recommended to the Provisional Ruling Council the adoption of
the 1979 constitution with relevant amendement from the 1995
draft constitution."
</P>
<P>
The 1979 constitution was promulgated for the civilian
government of Alhaji Shehu Shagari which ruled from 1979 to 1983
and known as the Second Republic.
</P>
<P>
It provides for the presidential system of government, with a
vice-president and a multi-party system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
