-- On the eve of the launching of euro, a first false note of
the New Europe has been heard as the president of the European
Central Bank, Dutchman Wim Duisenberg, ruled out leaving his post
in mid-term to hand it to Frenchman Jean-Claude Trichet, as he
had promised in May.
</P>
<P>
-- Despite falls in the autumn, the major stock exchanges in
Europe saw tremendous successes in the year 1998, with stock
indices rising by from 45.3 percent -- which is the highest -- in
Brussels to 14.5 percent in London. The Paris Bourse enjoyed a
rise in a third consecutive year with a 31.5 percent rise of its
CAS 40 index. 
