<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Inflation Over 80 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Inflation in Russia reached
84.4 percent in 1998, compared with 11 percent in 1997, the
Russian State Statistics Committee said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The high inflation was attributed to the three financial
crises and two government reshuffles this year, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price in December rose faster than that in
November -- 11.6 percent against 5.7 percent. The average daily
price rise stood at 0.355 percent in December against 0.184
percent in November, said the committee.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foodstuffs in 1998 became 96.9 percent more
expensive (compared with 9.1 percent in 1997) and the prices on
non-food items went up 99.5 percent compared with 8.1 percent in
1997. Tariffs and services went up 18.3 percent against 22.5
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, inflation was 109.6 percent in 1998, which means
that prices rose by 2.1 times, while in St.Petersburg prices went
up 78.0 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The inflation was 131.3 percent in 1995, 215.1 percent in
1994, 839.9 percent in 1993, 2,508.8 percent in 1992, and 160.4
percent in 1991, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
