<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mortality Among Children Declines in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) ranks second after Oman among developing countries in the
speed of reducing mortality among children below five years of age.
</P>
<P>
According to the UN Development Program's Human Development
Report 1998, the UAE's mortality among children aged below five
fell from 150 per 1,000 live births in 1970 to 19 in 1995, a drop
of 87 percent.
</P>
<P>
Broader access to health services, safe water and sanitation
and mobilization of public action for immunization are the
reasons for the fall in the country's mortality amogn children.
</P>
<P>
The life expectancy of the UAE nationals is 74.4 years in 1995,
according to the UNDP report. Regionally, Bahrain has a lower life
expectancy of 72.2 years.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP report estimates that the UAE population will
increase by 1.6 percent from 2.2 million in 1995 to 3 million by
the year 2015. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
