<HEADLINE> Zambia's Population Project Obtains UNFPA's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Population
Fund (UNFPA) decided to give Zambia 382,000 U.S. Dollars to
support its population project under an accord signed between the
UNFPA and the Zambian government here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Money will go to the project called "communication support
to population activities" through the Zambia Information Service.
</P>
<P>
The project is vital for the smooth implementation of
population programs as well as to inform the public about
population issues, Zambian Budget and Economic Affairs Permanent
Secretary, Boniface Nonde said at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Nonde said that information flow will help promote greater
participation in decision making among leaders and the general
public on population issues as they relate to gender, environment
and other developmental issues.
</P>
<P>
He said the project will contribute to raising the living
standards of the country's population in the next three years,
the Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same function, UNFPA's representative,
Margaret O'Challaghan said that UNFPA's support is focused on
making people understand the role that population issues play in
national development. These issues will affect the quality of
people's lives, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
