<HEADLINE> No Imminent Iraq-U.S. Showdown: Saudi Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and the United
States are not heading for "an imminent fresh crisis," said a
Saudi Arabian official Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The current confrontations in the no-fly zones in the northern
and southern Iraq "is just due to a misunderstanding," said Prince
Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz, Saudi Second Deputy Prime Minister, the
Kuwait News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had claimed that it had shot down two U.S. warplanes, but
Washington strongly denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan, also Minister of Defense and Aviation, advised
the Iraqi leadership to "understand the interest of their people."
</P>
<P>
He said that his country supports the call for lifting the
eight-year-old U.N. sanctions on Iraq, but "this is conditional to
agreeing and implementing the U.N. resolutions to serve their
country and its interest."
</P>
<P>
The Saudi defense chief said that the United States did not ask
for using Saudi territories " to launch the recent air strikes on
Iraq", adding this is not acceptable to Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed sanctions on Iraq after its 1990
invasion of Kuwait. And the United States and Britain launched air
strikes against Iraq in mid-December for alleged Iraq's
non-cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
