<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New System to Speed Check Clearance in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Clearing House transactions
in Kenya are set for a major revolution with further
implementation of the Magnetic Ink Character Recognition (MICR)
automated clearing in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We have already put in place the necessary systems to ensure
electronic clearing of checks from the central clearing house
based in Nairobi," Thursday's Daily Nation newspaper quoted the
MICR project manager Michael Karanja Bedan as saying.
</P>
<P>
Karanja said that the first phase of the automated clearing
project, debit clearing, has been in place since May this year.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the MICR project, credit clearing, will be
piloted from January 1999 and further implementation will depend
on the success of the process, he said.
</P>
<P>
This phase will herald an almost "paperless" transaction
regime, reducing the traction time below the four days targeted
in the initial phase for all checks.
</P>
<P>
"The ultimate aim should be to attain real-time settlements,"
said the manager.
</P>
<P>
Bank customers are expected to benefit from shorter check
clearance periods, especially in respect of the so-called
"up-country checks" that take as long as seven days to cash.
</P>
<P>
The MICR project is intended to speed up the process of contra
transactions between banks involving checks while creating
much-desired uniformity, according to Daily Nation.
</P>
<P>
The project involves the printing by all banks of an
electronic code line on all checks, so that they are recognizable
to special readers installed in banks reducing the time wasted in
physical checks.
</P>
<P>
The paper said central to the project is the centralization of
check clearance from the regional centers to Nairobi, the capital
of the eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
The MICR code line includes such details as check member,
bank, branch and the check digit, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
