<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post-Flood Resettlement Gets International Aids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Ye Zhangrong and his family bid
farewell to 1998 as well as to their life of huddling in a tent
for months by moving into his new residence recently.
</P>
<P>
A victim of severe summer floods which destroyed millions of
houses, the 55-year-old farmer saw some 110 two-storey buildings
nearby are also in the final stage of construction.
</P>
<P>
Ye and 590 of his fellow villagers in Xinzhou County, central
China's Hubei Province, benefited from a three-million-yuan
donation from Lions Clubs International, the world's largest
service club organization.
</P>
<P>
The funds were used to build roads, water and power supply
networks and telecommunication facilities in the new village,
named "Lions Village". Every household was subsidized by local
government to cover one fourth of the costs for housing
construction, according to the village head Ye Fangxin.
</P>
<P>
"I feel much safer now," said Ye, whose former home inside the
levees of the Yangtze River had been inundated twice in flood
seasons of the past three years.
</P>
<P>
In areas along the Yangtze, China's longest river, a prolonged
problem is that some residents have settled inside the levees so
as to get more land to tilt and this was cited as one of the
causes for successive floodings.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has time and again pursuaded these
residents to move to safer locations, in an effort to make way for
possible flood water flows.
</P>
<P>
The design of Lions Village complies with the government's
decision, and should be a good example for rebuilding of housing
in other flood-hit areas, said He Xinghua, an official with the
Ministry of Construction in charge of urban and rural planning.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the design and planning work has been finished
for construction of 2,500 villages in Hubei and six other
provinces, the major flooded regions last summer.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of flood victims across China are expected to
move into their new residences before the Spring Festival, a
traditional year-end festival for family reunion, which falls on
February 16, next year.
</P>
<P>
"Helping the rest of the flood victims to spend their winter at
their own home will also be the most important job for the
government," He Xinghua said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
