<HEADLINE> Famine Threatens as Drought Persists in Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people living in
northern Kenya are facing severe food shortage as failure of the
short rains has caused a severe drought there, local leaders
warned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Thursday quoted more than 40 county
and town councillors in Wajir District as saying that the drought
is taking its toll on livestock in the area inhabited mainly by
pastoralist communities.
</P>
<P>
The civic leaders said that if the situation facing our people
does not change soon, they and their livestock will die of hunger
and thirst.
</P>
<P>
The areas of Arbajanhan, Hadado, Giriftu, Dambas, Wajir-Bor
and Eldaas are said to be the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Minister of the Cooperative Development Ministry,
Mohamed Abdi Affey also expressed concern at the parliament
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the drought which, he said, could be precursor to the
La Nina weather phenomenon, milk yields have substantially
declined, creating an urgent need for food aid in the area.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, most bore-holes and other ground water reservoirs
have dried up, causing a critical water shortage there, Affey
noted.
</P>
<P>
He called for urgent action to rehabilitate the water supply
to avert conflict among the pastoralist communities scrambling
for the little water available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
