<HEADLINE> Singapore PM Says 1999 Will Be Another Difficult Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong expected that 1999 will be another difficult year for
Singapore and he called upon the nation to stay united to overcome
challenges.
</P>
<P>
In his new year message released at noon on Thursday, Goh said
1998 has been a difficult year for Singapore and 1999 will be
another difficult year.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister said his country's economic growth for the
fourth quarter of 1998 was again negative, contracting 1.9 percent
on adjusted quarter-on-quarter bases and bringing the economic
growth for 1998 as a whole down to 1.3 percent from the 7.8
percent of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Citing the Singapore Ministry of Trade and Industry's forecast
that Singapore economy should grow by between minus one percent
and plus one percent in 1999, Goh said "the prospects are very
uncertain."
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister underlined that his country's security and
economic recovery will be affected by regional economic climate
and political events abroad, adding "these political problems may
have unhappy consequences-- social disorder, regional instability,
and uncontrolled flows of illegal immigrants."
</P>
<P>
Goh said Singapore can not avoid some further retrenchments
despite the economic package announced in November to reduce
business costs and strengthen competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
He also drew attention to his expectation that the U.S. economy
may slow down next year and make it harder for Singapore to boost
its exports.
</P>
<P>
Noting Singaporeans have become used to high growth since the
1985 recession, the Prime Minister warned the whole nation "not to
take things for granted" and urged them "to be alert to what goes
on in the region and the major countries" and to respond nimbly to
changing conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
