<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Auto Makers Deeper Rooted in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- With the first batch of
Buick cars coming off the production line of General Motors in
Shanghai recently, China at last has the capability to
manufacture the world's latest luxurious cars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile in this showcase of China's economic growth, but on
the other side of the Huangpu River that runs through the city,
the construction of a car testing track and research and
development center for Volkswagen's Shanghai operation is
approaching completion.
</P>
<P>
The differences yet similarities between the two projects are
obvious.
</P>
<P>
The Buick project is GM's first in Shanghai but it plans to
raise the annual production capacity to 100,000 luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Volkswagen Automotive Company Ltd., Santana model
is now 14 years old. A mid-range model, it was marketed in the
mid 1980s in major industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
The current production capacity of the Santana in Shanghai is
up to 300,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
The two joint projects share the same partner: Shanghai Automot
ive Industry (Group) Corp. (SAIC)
</P>
<P>
Many auto industry observers are speculating about the impact
they will have on each other, said SAIC President Chen Xianglin,
but both of them see their respective new endeavors as a
cornerstone for their commitment to China's auto industry. This
is evidence that China's automobile industry, with Shanghai as
its center, has become "an important arena for competition among
the world's auto giants."
</P>
<P>
"Shanghai VW has a long-term plan for its presence in China,"
Chen said,which is why it made a 1.6 billion yuan investment in
the technical center and the car testing track, which will become
China's first modern testing facility.
</P>
<P>
The founding of Shanghai VW in 1984 is considered the starting
point for China's modern auto industry. It is the most profitable
VW joint venture in the world and has so far produced 1.15
million cars, capturing half of China's domestic market share.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai VW is currently developing the third generation
Santana, whose two predecessors have made remarkable sales
achievements in China.
</P>
<P>
The first of the new models is expected to roll off the
production lines in a year, and mass production will begin in
2000.
</P>
<P>
According to Peter Loew, vice general manager of Shanghai VW,
the company's research and development center in Shanghai will
employ 600-800 engineers over the next few years. He expects the
center to be compared to VW's other two centers in Germany and
Brazil by then.
</P>
</TEXT>
