<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, on December 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and Russian
President Boris Yeltsin Wednesday agreed to disagree over U.S.
air strikes against Iraq so that the two countries could move the
common agenda forward in 1999, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called Yeltsin from the Oval Office before leaving on
a New Year's vacation in South Carolina, White House spokesman
David Leavy said. They talked about 40 minutes. "Both presidents
agreed that despite differences over Iraq, it was important to
continue to build the U.S.-Russian relationship and to move the
important common agenda that we have forward in 1999," Leavy
said.Yeltsin has strongly criticized U.S.-British bombings
against Iraq on Dec. 16-19, insisting there was no justification
for using force.(US-Iraq-Russia )
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on Wednesday
night called on his people to try their best in the coming new
year to safeguard the nation's freedom and independence.
</P>
<P>
In his New Year message to the nation, read on state
television, Milosevic stressed that all Yugoslav people, along
with their leaders, are determined to bring about a political
solution to the Kosovo problem, so that all ethnic groups in the
province can live together in harmony, based on the principle of
equality to all.(Yugoslavia-Address)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombian President Andres Pastrana on
Wednesday reaffirmed that he would participate in the opening
ceremony of the peace talks with the leftist Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia (FARC) starting on January 7.
</P>
<P>
But FARC founder and leader Manuel Marulanda Velez, 68, did
not confirm whether he would attend a scheduled meeting with
Pastrana in fear of his safety despite a government pledge that
the veteran rebel leader would be protected by 60 members of Pa
strana's presidential guards.The peace talks will be held in the
southern Caquete department, an area which extends over more than
42,000 kilometers and has been demilitarized for three
months.(Colombia-President)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albanian Defense Minister Luan Hajdaraga said here
Wednesday that on-going clashes between the armed forces of
ethnic Albanians in the Serbian province of Kosovo and police
forces are likely to intensify in the spring.
</P>
<P>
 Speaking at a joint conference with his Greek counterpart
Akis Xohaxopoulos, Hajdaraga said the Albanian government held
that the Kosovo crisis should be settled through peaceful
means.If the international community fails to figure out a
diplomatic solution, Hajdaraga said, the escalating armed
conflicts between the two sides in Kosovo will probably intensify
in the spring.(Albania-Kosovo-Intensification) 
</P>
