<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top 10 Sports Events of China in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
1. China won 129 gold medals in the 13th Asian Games in
Bangkok from December 6-20, topping the medal standings for the
fifth consecutive time since 1982.
</P>
<P>
2. The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region won five golds,
six silvers and six bronzes in its first Asian Games after China
resumed sovereignty over it on July 1, 1997. The 5-6-6 record
was its best ever performance in the Games.
</P>
<P>
3. As part of the National Fitness Program, 237 urban
communities in China built a total of 511 public sports
facilities.
</P>
<P>
4. China failed to end its winter Olympic Games gold drought
in the Nagano Games in February, returning home with six silver
medals, five from speedskating.
</P>
<P>
5. Gymnast Sang Lan was paralyzed from an injury sustained in
a training session at the Fourth Goodwill Games in New York. The
17-year-old girl showed great courage in adversity.
</P>
<P>
6. Chinese women won the team title at the 33rd Chess
Olympiad. It was the first team title China won in a major
international chess competition.
</P>
<P>
7. Chinese volleyball made a remarkable progress as the women
spikers finished runners-up in the World Championships while the
men's team returned to the top form. The two teams also won golds
at the Bangkok Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
8. Seven Chinese strongwomen broke 13 world records as they
made a clean sweep of the gold medals in the women's
weightlifting at the Bangkok Asian Games. Liu Xiuhua captured
the first gold for China at the Games by winning the women's 48kg
category title. This was the third consecutive time that China's
first Asian Games gold was grabbed by a women weightlifter.
</P>
<P>
9. Chinese men's table tennis players met a strong challenge
from their Asian and European rivals as they failed to win the
singles title in the World Cup and the Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
10. Blood test was introduced to the national track cycling
finals in Nanjing in September, a sign that China has stepped up
efforts in its fight against doping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
