<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Auto Makers Deeper Rooted in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"GM has been eyeing the Chinese car market for many years,"
Chen said, "and now the world's No. 1 auto producer, though a
latecomer compared to VW, started its car making operations in
China with up to date models and technology.
</P>
<P>
Supported by 270 local auto part manufacturers, 40 percent of
the parts of the Shanghai joint venture Buick are made in China;
and the ratio is expected to rise to 80 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
Within the joint venture agreement, apart from producing three
separate Buick models, Shanghai GM will have introduced all the
technologies needed for production, as well as related GM
technological innovations, within the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Shanghai has more than 30 joint ventures involved
in making cars and car parts with a combined foreign investment
of 2.07 billion U.S. dollars, from as the United States, Germany,
Britain, Japan and France.
</P>
<P>
But the Shanghai business is only part of the picture.
Different new models are being developed or sold, and new
production lines are being built, in other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts call 1998 the "model changing year" for
China's auto industry.
</P>
<P>
VW's joint venture in northeast China's Changchun city, the
First Automotive Works-Volkswagen, launched this year its new Jet
ta and Audi models.
</P>
<P>
And Dongfeng-Citroen Automobile Co., Ltd. in Wuhan, has begun
to market its third generation "Fukang" model in China.
</P>
<P>
The newly established Guangzhou Honda Automobile Co., Ltd., a
joint investment between Guangzhou Automobile Group and the Honda
Co., has already begun a trial production of the latest Accord
series sedan and start full time production next October.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that despite the leveling of growth in China's
car market due to the ongoing Asian Financial Crisis,it will
still have the most growth potential in the next decade. This,
together with China's expected eventual admission to the World
Trade Organization, are the incentives for the world's major auto
manufacturers to become even more active in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
