<HEADLINE> NBA Players Lose Bid to Play in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Three NBA players were not
allowed to play the rest of the season in Europe by a federal
judge today in Houston.
</P>
<P>
Nick Van Exel of the Denver Nuggets, Marcus Camby of the New
York Knicks and Reggis Slater of the Toronto Raptors had sued the
NBA and USA Basketball, accusing both entities preventing them to
finish the season in Europe even if the lockout ended.
</P>
<P>
After a hearing, U.S. District Judge Simeon Lake rejected the
players' bid but said they were entitled to arbitration. They
have contacted arbitrator John Feerick in an effort to have the
case heard tomorrow or Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the opportunity," said agent James Bryant, who
represents all three players. "The problem has been until now
there has been no remedy anywhere. It's a victory to have the
opportunity to present that."
</P>
<P>
American players cannot play overseas without clearance form
USA Basketball. All three players have one year left on their NBA
contracts. 
</P>
