<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Shipping Corporation on Brink of Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The state-owned Bangladesh
Shipping Corporation (BSC) has reached the point of brink of
collapse owing to huge financial liabilities and operational
setbacks.
</P>
<P>
The tottering condition of the firm is attributed to lack of
efficient management, failure to procure uptodate vessels and
purchasing vessels on unequal terms in many cases, taking loans on
high interest and finally misuse and mishandling of assets, The
New Nation daily Thursday quoted official sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The accumulated loss of the BSC has stood at nearly 2.16
billion taka (44.5 million U.S. dollars) while it owes 1.8 billion
taka (37.1 million dollars) to banks.
</P>
<P>
The BSC could not add a single vessel to its fleet during the
past 10 years, they said, adding the BSC rather sold out 13 ships
from its 38-ship fleet built up earlier.
</P>
<P>
The only mother tanker of the BSC fleet was sold in 1982 and no
replacement of the tanker has so far been made to make it worthy
to meet the present day needs.
</P>
<P>
The plight of BSC had started in early 1980s when a number of
private shipping companies started their journey by taking away a
number of skilled personnel from the BSC team.
</P>
<P>
From then on, the BSC started lagging behind in installation of
modern equipment in its ships, and it is now staying far behind
the international level in terms of technical facilities.
</P>
<P>
The BSC started its operation in 1972 as a local agent of
foreign cargo companies with a paid up capital of 450 million taka
(9.28 million dollars). Later it managed to procure vessels
largely with financial assistance from banks and other
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The corporation made profit during the first 13 years of its
operation but now it has become a white elephant owing to huge
losses during the last 13 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Beijingers Focus on Science and Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey revealed that
young Beijingers are more interested in scientific and
technological development than in the basic science.
</P>
<P>
The younger generation is not only interested in the
development of communication technology and innovative daily
necessities, but also in biology, medical and military science and
space technology, according to the survey conducted by Beijing
Shaohai Market Research Company.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey indicated that younger people living in the
nation's political and cultural center are somewhat indifferent to
physics and agricultural science.
</P>
<P>
The survey of young people between 14-35 years of age was
designed to study scientific awareness. Some 29 percent of the
respondents were college graduates, 43 percent were in high school
and 28 percent were below the junior high level.
</P>
<P>
Youngsters with higher education levels exhibited greater
interest in science, with males exhibiting a greater
interest than females.
</P>
<P>
Young Beijingers are not only familiar with "cloning" and the
"information highway", and also exhibit greater competence in
terms of operating principles for mobile phones, cameras,
refrigerators and washing machines than in scientific and
technical terms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
