<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Weathers Global Crisis, But Reforms Slacken </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Looking back on the year
1998, one could see that though India has weathered the global
economic crisis, it's economic reforms have slackened, 'The
Statesman' said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the calibrated pace of reforms adopted by India
since 1991, the country escaped a great deal of the convulsions
that shook East Asia and countries further afield. As its economy
was not fully integrated with the world, especially with the rupee
convertibility confined to the current account transactions, the
country escaped relatively unscathed," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"But that does not give much cause for optimism. The great
Indian economic reform had almost ground to a halt in the
pre-election year of 1995 when the initiator of the reform, then
the former Finance Minister, Dr. Manmohan Singh, applied the
brakes...... There has not been change after the coalition
stitched together by the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) took office
nine months ago," it said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha in his 1998-99 Budget unveiled
on June 1 this year "made tall promises, but nobody believes that
the targets then outlined will be realized during this financial
year ending March 1999".
</P>
<P>
"For instance, Mr. Sinha had set a target of reducing fiscal
deficit to 5.6 percent of GDP by March 1999 and he had held on to
that goal with nothing more concrete than blind faith. Mr. Sinha
has now been forced to admit that the fiscal deficit will exceed
his magic figure and all he is prepared to venture is that it
would be less than seven percent," it further said.
</P>
<P>
"Industrial production in 1998-99 (April 1, 1998-March 31,
1999) has fallen much below the expectations of eight to 10
percent forecast by the government. The increase for the first
seven months of fiscal 1998-99 is estimated at 3.6 percent
compared to last year's 6.2 percent for the same period," it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
