<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flowers Thrive Despite Cold Tibet Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- People in the Tibet Autonomous
Region enjoy potted plants throughout frigid winter weather.
</P>
<P>
"Generations of our ancestors were serfs. We personally won the
right to own a home following the abolishment of serfdom, but
lacked the financial resources to do so at the time. Things are
quite different now however and our annual income ranges between
40,000 to 50,000 yuan (4,800-6,000 US dollars), said Lhasa
resident Zhoima Yangjim.
</P>
<P>
Zhoima's hope for a new home finally became true last
year. Some 30-odd potted plants, including Chinese flowering
crabapple, bamboo and plum, decorate three balconies and the
living room. A potted oleander sits in the center of the living
room, with Chinese wisteria plants sitting beside the sofa and on
the wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
"The beautiful plants help to purify the air and provide a good
atmosphere the year round," according to Zhoima.
</P>
<P>
Flowers were once the sole domain of aristocratic
families. However, the abolishment of the serfdom provided
ordinary Tibetans with the opportunity to build homes and flowers
have gained increasing popularity since the 1980s. Local residents
have indeed enjoyed a better life over the past 20 years of
reform and opening.
</P>
<P>
Temples in Tibet are also filled with the fragrance of
flowers. Resident monks water and prune the plants each day after
morning prayers.
</P>
<P>
"Colorful flowers have brought great happiness to us."
according to Rinqing, a lama in the Daipung Monastery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
