<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Strengthens Animal Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- An additional 14 species of
wild animals in northeast China's Liaoning Province have been
placed under the national protection in recent years as a result
of the provincial government's extensive wildlife protection
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China was once home to over 1,000 species of wild
animals and was well-known for abundant ginseng, martens and
pilose antlers. However, excessive hunting for both food and
materials for traditional Chinese medicine led to a decrease in
the number of wild animals.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has introduced a series of concrete
plant and animal protection measures since the 1980s. For example,
Liaoning has established a bird protection week and wild animal
protection month. The province has also conducted
extensive spring and autumn publicity campaigns on preventing
forest fires.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has also formulated a series of regulations and
established a comprehensive legal system covering wild animal
protection. Twelve hunting regulations have broadened the scope of
wildlife protection, and a total of 91 wild species have been
placed under provincial protection.
</P>
<P>
Seven national and 14 provincial nature reserves covering
145,000 ha have been established in Liaoning since the 1978
implementation of policies which prohibited hunting, and the
establishment of forest and wild animal nature reserves. The long
list of reserves includes Dalian Snake Island, as well as a
waterfowl reserve in Panjin and the Dongya Chinese Pine Forest
Reserve in Jinzhou.
</P>
<P>
Manchurian tigers, sable, black bears and hazel grouse have
reappeared since the establishment of nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
Local residents are conscientiously protecting wild
animals, with statistics showing that more than 280
animals have been rescued and returned to various reserves in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has also expanded cooperation and technological
exchanges with the World Wildlife Fund and the International Crane
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The Liaoning Department of Forestry noted plans to establish 20
more nature reserves by the year 2000, and will extend great
effort to ensure that wild animals enjoy a safe habitat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
