<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary to Have Anti-Y2K Plan Ready in January 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian government
will have a plan ready by mid next January to tackle the computer
millennium problem, earmarking 325 million forints (1.5 million
U.S. dollars) under the 1999 budget as the central control fund
for the plan, the Vilaggazdasag newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Computer systems in the sectors of energy, finance,
communication, national defense and health have been selected as
priorities for checking and debugging, the report quoted a
government official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official, deputy state secretary in charge of information
management in the prime minister's office Roska Marietta, said
the national railway, post and telecommunications, as well as
some foreign funded banks had already started to fix the
millennium glitch more than a year ago, planning to complete the
work by mid next year.
</P>
<P>
The report said threats from the Y2K problem are relatively
slight in Hungary, where computers are not as widespread as in
West European countries.
</P>
<P>
However, other experts are less optimistic. Officials with
the Interior Ministry said billions of forints would be needed to
debug the computers of their ministry alone.
</P>
<P>
Some experts warned that the government's allotted fund is far
from enough, estimating that another eight billion forints (37.2
million dollars) would have to be drawn out from the 1999 budget
to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem results from a flaw in early computer
programming, which uses two digits to record years, like 98, 99.
Such computers can recognize only the last two digits of a year
and will fail on January 1, 2000, when they will assume it is
1900 and may start spewing out flawed data at the turn of the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
Governments of some countries began to prepare for the pote
ntial outbreak of the millennium problem as far back as 10 years
ago while global spending on fixing the problem is expected to
reach between 300 billion and 600 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
