<HEADLINE> Indonesian Company Invests in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- An Indonesian company has
signed an agreement with Sri Lanka for a project with investment
up to Rs. 800 million (11.76 million U.S. dollars) at the Mirigama
Export Processing Zone, about 70 kilometers northeast of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed Thursday with the Board of
Investment (BOI), Jembo Cable and Wire Limited will manufacture
aluminium redraw rods and aluminium and copper cables to meet Sri
Lanka's domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
More than the domestic market, the company in the long run will
also explore overseas for their products in the Middle East,
Thailand and particularly in the South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The project, scheduled to be implemented in three stages, will
set up a high tech plant in a 15 acre land at the export zone.
</P>
<P>
Under the first stage 15,000 tons of aluminium rods will be
produced annually for the Electricity Board and private cable
manufacturers who import these for two million dollars at present.
</P>
<P>
In the second stage it will produce aluminium cables to meet
the domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
During the third stage investment will be increased from Rs.
425 million to Rs. 800 million, copper cables will be produced for
the telecommunications sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
