<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian President to Attend Peace Talks With Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Andres Pastrana on Wednesday reaffirmed that he would participate
in the opening ceremony of the peace talks with the leftist
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) starting on January
7.
</P>
<P>
But FARC founder and leader Manuel Marulanda Velez, 68, did
not confirm whether he would attend a scheduled meeting with
Pastrana in fear of his safety despite a government pledge that
the veteran rebel leader would be protected by 60 members of Pa
strana's presidential guards.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks will be held in the southern Caquete
department, an area which extends over more than 42,000
kilometers and has been demilitarized for three months.
</P>
<P>
Government representatives and multilateral organization
delegates, as well as personalities such as Guatemalan activist
and Nobel Peace Prize laureate Rigoberta Menchu, have been
invited to attend the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Journalist Jose Vicente Rangel, a representative of Venezuelan
president-elect Hugo Chavez, will also attend the opening
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the National Liberation Army (ELN), the second
largest guerrilla group after the FARC, will also attend the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The FARC's security measures will include a ban on selling and
consuming alcohol and restrictions on the number of cars and
planes.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of people have died during the 36 years of
civil war in Colombia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
