<HEADLINE> Indonesian Female Athlete Cashes in on Her Gold Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian female athlete
Supriati Sutono received 100 million rupiah (12,500 U.S. dollars)
in cash bonuses from the Indonesian Amateur Athletic Federation
(PASI) for her success in winning gold medal at the 13th Asian
Games.
</P>
<P>
Supriati confounded pundits' prediction when she won the
5,000 meters run in a time of 15:54.45 on the penultimate day of
the Games.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy with the bonus," said Supriati after the
hand-out ceremony held in the presence of Chairman of the
Indonesian Sports Council (KONI) Wismoyo Arismunandar here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Supriati has now set her eyes on the Olympics
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
"I will run until someone deserves to take my place in the
national team. And I will be happy to end my athletics career
when I have competed in the Olympics," she was quoted by the
Indonesian Observer Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Supriati's gold ended a 36-year wait, ever since 1962 , when
Sarengat, now a KONI officer, stole the show with his 100 meters
victory in Jakarta. Supriati has also contributed to the
contingent's success in reaching the target of six golds set
prior to the event.
</P>
<P>
Supriati's coach Nicky Pattiasina shared the windfall with
his 50 million rupiah bonus. Three other athletics coaches, along
with medical team and athletics federation workers received a
smaller bonus.
</P>
<P>
Another 100 million rupiah of the cash went to the Secapa
track and field in Bandung, where Supriati undertook her daily
training. "We want to stress that Supriati's success also owes
much to team work from various parties," said Kunarto, a PASI
official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
