<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mia Audina Must Get Her Act Together, Says Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's best current
hope in badminton Mia Audina must be able to put aside all her
problems if she wants to qualify for the Olympics in Sydney, said
coach Liang Chiusia.
</P>
<P>
Liang Chiusia said a champion should not involve her personal
problems in training and competition.
</P>
<P>
"We all have problems but a champion must put aside her
personal problems during a competition. She must also concentrate
fully during training and not think about them", Liang was quoted
by the Jakarta Post Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mia's performance has been dropping off lately. Her crucial
lapse was made in the women's team event in the just-concluded
13th Asian Games in Bangkok where she lost to South Korean Kim
Ji-hyun in the women's team semifinals.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Mia has been concerned lately about her
mother's health. Her mother is suffering kidney failure and must
undergo dialysis treatment twice a week.
</P>
<P>
Her poor relationship with her father Rivan Tjiptawan also
influenced her form. Rivan used to be Mia's idol during her youth.
</P>
<P>
Mia's close relationship with boyfriend Tylio Lobman, a Dutch
gospel singer, has been blamed for her declining form. But she
has refuted this and said that Tylio has been boosting her
fighting spirit.
</P>
<P>
"She must overcome her personal problems, otherwise they will
give her trouble and disturb her concentration," Liang said.
</P>
<P>
Liang said she was really shocked by Mia's failure in the
Asiad.
</P>
<P>
"She never told me that she was nervous and scared. If only
she had told me before playing, I could have helped her by giving
advice," she said.
</P>
<P>
Liang compared Mia to former world number one Susi Susanti,
now retired due to her pregnancy, who often confided with her
about her feelings before competing.
</P>
<P>
"Mia is only 19 years old but her problems are very complex.
Unfortunately, she rarely tells me about them and so I can't help
her," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
