<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Give Minimum 11 Years' Education for All </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 31 (Xinhua) -- All students in Malaysia
will be given a minimum 11 years' public education instead of the
current nine years.
</P>
<P>
This is another history created in the education system in
Malaysia when a 100 percent of students can continue with their
education into the higher secondary schools, Education Minister
Najib Tun Razak told a press conference here Wednesday, according
to national press reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Najib announced that those who failed in all subjects in the
lower secondary examination (after nine years) will be offered
places in vocational secondary schools to continue their studies
with the start of next year's school session for a minimum of 11
years.
</P>
<P>
Najib said his ministry made the decision as it did not want
any student to drop out of the country's education system and if
a student drops out, it will not be for the good of the country
nor for the student himself.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the ministry would not stop any of the
academically weak students from rejecting the offer for a place in
the vocational secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that in the vocational schools, the students
can pick up technical certificates in various fields such as in
electrical services, radio and television servicing, welding and
motor maintenance.
</P>
<P>
Najib said the Education Ministry would redeploy teachers
trained in critical subjects -- English language, science and
mathematics -- to overcome the shortage of such teachers in
schools especially in the rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
