<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Approved Investment in 1998 Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Domestic and Foreign
investment projects that had been approved by the Indonesian
government in 1998 were declined, State Minister of Investment and
Chairman of the Investment Coordinating Agency Hamzah Haz said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The approved domestic investment projects in 1998 were
estimated at 59.4 trillion rupiah (7.4 billion U.S. dollars), a
decline compared to the 119.9 trillion rupiah in 1997, while the
number of projects also dropped by 57.1 percent to 308 compared to
718 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The domestic economic, political and security situation in the
country has a serious bearing on the prospective investors'
decision whether or not to make an investment in Indonesia," the
minister was quoted by Antara News Agency Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the approvals that had been issued to foreign
investment projects this year were estimated at 13.3 billion U.S.
dollars, a decline of 60.7 percent compared to the 33.8 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997, but the number of projects increased by 23.9
percent to 979 projects compared to the 790 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the approved foreign investment projects in
1998 is an indication that most of the foreign investors were very
well versed with the market, so that even in the current
protracted economic crisis they were able to plot feasible
investment opportunities, while their local counterparts still
have difficulties in making use of the existing opportunities,
Hamzah said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the domestic investment projects covered
transportation, office buildings and telecommunications, while
most of the foreign investment projects covered services.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the foreign investment projects belonged to
investors from the United Kingdom estimated at 4.8 billion U.S.
dollars with 49 projects, Singapore 1.3 billion U.S. dollars with
118 projects, and Japan worth 1.2 billion U.S. dollars with 73
projects, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The country with the biggest investment in Indonesia is Japan
with 1,066 projects worth 42.6 billion U.S. dollars, followed by
the United Kingdom with 282 projects estimated at 37.7 billion
U.S. dollars and Singapore with 820 projects estimated at 20.2
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of investment prospects in 1999, Hamzah said that
improved political stability as the result of the June 1999
general election as well as the general session of the People's
Consultative Assembly to form a new government in accordance with
the aspirations of the people, will encourage more investors to
build their projects in Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
