<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Grows Colored Cotton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, the nation's leading cotton production
base, has successfully developed new strains of cotton featuring
13 colors.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Junlu Group recently announced that it achieved a
1998 output of 171 tons of colored cotton on 2,000 mu (133.33 ha),
with per-mu production approaching the normal level of 85
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The new strains are free of chemical pigment which results from
dyeing. The worldwide production for colored cotton stands at
20,000 tons a year, or one percent of total output. However, the
proportion is expected to reach 30 percent within 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Projections for Xinjiang's 1998 ginned cotton output to hit
1.24 million tons, with the region accounting for some 30 percent
of total output nationally and six percent worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Junlu introduced three colored cotton strains from the
U.S. to experimental plots in Gansu and Sichuan provinces in 1994,
with the per mu output hovering at 30 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Chinese research institutes developed 11 color strain that Junlu
currently grows on the basis of imported varieties.
</P>
<P>
Over 100,000 of Junlu's colored cotton garments are available
in stores in many major cities, including Beijing, Shanghai and
Dalian.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang plans to grow colored cotton on 20,000 mu during 1999,
with output expected to reach 1,710 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Gets Cleaner Water from Mainland Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Hong Kong will
soon have access to purer water from a water supply project in
neighboring Shenzhen, where a major treatment plant was put into
trial operation on December 21.
</P>
<P>
The system now in use, the Dongshen water supply project, was
built in 1964, and is used to provide fresh water to some 10
million people living in Hong Kong and the cities of Shenzhen and
Dongguan in Guangdong Province by drawing water from the Dongjiang
River, and sending it to the Yantian and Shenzhen reservoirs via
the natural course of the Shima River.
</P>
<P>
Due to economic development in the Pearl River Delta over the
past two decades and the drastic increase of industrial activity
and population, various polluting sources around the water supply
project are on rise, and the water in the Shima River has become
seriously polluted.
</P>
<P>
According to Ru Jianhui, engineer-in-chief of the Guangdong
Provincial Water Conservation Bureau, the new plant, built at the
entrance of Shenzhen reservoir at a cost of 350 million yuan, can
reduce the amounts of major pollutants such as ammonia and nitrogen
by 50 to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province has also adopted other measures to improve
the quality of water from the Dongshen water supply project,
including spending 350 million yuan to construct a pumping
station on the Dongjiang River.
</P>
<P>
This station, which was put into service in September, will
reduce the volume of pollutants around the previous water-drawing
spot by 60 to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has also approved another plan to
install a special pipeline for sending water directly from the
Dongjiang River to the Shenzhen reservoir. This plan, together
with a feasibility study report, has been submitted to the State
Development Planning Commission for approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wenzhou: Window on China's Private Sector (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Over the past 20 years there
has been no other place in China quite like the city of Wenzhou
in eastern Zhejiang Province, a town often in dispute about
whether its local economy reflects capitalism or socialism.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Wenzhou has become a heaven of China's private economy.
</P>
<P>
More than one-tenth of Wenzhou's families were engaged in
private businesses ten years ago, and many of the so-called
collectively owned enterprises were actually private businesses.
</P>
<P>
Now, Wenzhou has some 40,000 private businesses, with an
output value accounting of more than 90 percent of the city's total
industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
A senior local official said that the private economy has
become a major force in the service sector, and also a leading
investor in science and technology, education, culture, public
health and sports.
</P>
<P>
He said the farmers in Wenzhou have a tradition of doing
business to make up for insufficient farmland, as per
capita farmland is less than 0.033 hectare, far below the national
average.
</P>
<P>
" In the past forty years, the state has invested little here
because Wenzhou, close to Taiwan Province, is regarded as a
frontline," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have nothing to rely on but our own hands," said Xu
Shouguo, a millionaire farmer in the town of Yishan in Cangnan
county.
</P>
<P>
Driven by dire poverty, Xu set up a small printing house in
1975, but shortly thereafter he was severely punished for
reverting to capitalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wenzhou: Window on China's Private Sector (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With China's reform and opening up, Xu resumed the operation of
his printing house in 1980, and it has now become a joint-stock
business specializing in producing garment brands.
</P>
<P>
Xu's move was silently approved by the local government, but
his enterprise was called "collectively owned."
</P>
<P>
In 1989, Wenzhou faced more pressures as news reports said that
the private economy was the base of bourgeois
liberalization. Fearing that policy might change, many Wenzhou
entrepreneurs either shut down their businesses, went abroad, or
renamed their enterprises as collectively owned ones.
</P>
<P>
The Wenzhou Boyi Valve factory, which had worn the
collectively-owned label for 12 years, stopped wearing it last
year.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Chenming, the factory owner, said that not until 1992,
when paramount Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping asked the nation to
stop arguing about what is socialism and what is capitalism, did
private business owners in Wenzhou put more funds into their
operations.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said he will try to further raise the reputation of his
enterprise and compete in the international market.
</P>
<P>
A local official said that more and more household businesses
are evolving into joint-stock enterprises, and tend to rely more
on high technology in their development.
</P>
<P>
Private companies in Wenzhou are mostly engaged in such
industries as clothing, shoes, lamps, lighters, low-voltage
electrical appliances and valves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Sets Modernization Timetable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 31 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang
Province plans to achieve at least a moderate level of development
by the year 2020, according to plans unveiled during the recent
Tenth Zhejiang Provincial Communist Party Congress.
</P>
<P>
Plans call for the province to meet 12 indexes for
modernization. The list includes a per capita gross domestic
product (GDP) ranging from 3,000 to 5,000 US dollars; a 5-15
percent agricultural contribution to GDP; a non-farm population
accounting for 60-70 percent of the total work force; a 45-50
percent service sector contribution to the provincial GDP; and an
urbanization ratio of between 50-60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang, one of the most developed areas in China, has gained
recognition for successfully developing township-run enterprises,
as well as achievements in economic development.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang's 1998 GDP skyrocketed to 505 billion yuan, up from
only 23.29 billion yuan in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Deputies attending the provincial congress pledged to redouble
effort to accelerate expansion of Ningbo Port, including an
economic and technological development zone, Daxie Island and a
bonded zone, as well as improving the modernization level of
industries and urban areas, closing gaps between rural and urban
areas, improving living standards and exploring the marine
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
