<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zeal in Vegetable Growing up in East China's Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 31 (Xinhua) -- "I'm not worried about selling
the vegetables, we just fear that they may not grow well." said Qi
Baofang, a 28-year-old woman in the city of Shouguang in eastern
China's Shandong Province, who has rented an 800-square-meter
vegetable greenhouse to produce towel gourds.
</P>
<P>
Many local farmers have done the same thing. He Fengying
rented a 600-square-meter greenhouse to grow bottle gourds, which
will enable her to gain nearly 30,000 yuan (3,600
U.S.dollars). And Wang Delian uses his greenhouse to plant
potatoes introduced from Israel, with an annual yield of 40,000
kilograms and profits of 35,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Wang said she must work all day, from seven in the morning to
six in the evening, tending her vegetables in the greenhouse. But
she is quite satisfied, since it is quite profitable and she will
take gain back her investment after just one year of hard work.
</P>
<P>
The decision of the Third Plenary Session of the 15th CPC this
year to prolong the land contracts for another 30 years has
greatly inspired farmers to invest more money in their land. Each
greenhouse costs 20,000 to 30,000 yuan on average, still the
number of the farmers who take up vegetable growing is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Ren Zhiwu, vice manager of the 36.6-hectare vegetable wholesale
market in the city, noted that the market place has brought great
convenience to the growers since its establishment in 1984, and
that investments in the facilities have now reached nearly 200
million yuan. The farmers will also be able to swap their crops at
the market to satisfy the various needs of different
locations.
</P>
</TEXT>
