Foreman and Larry Holmes is not canceled. But a looming financial
deadline for $12.6 million puts it on a resuscitator.
</P>
<P>
Promoter Roger Levitt missed last week's deadline for
depositing letters of credit to preserve the planned January 23
fight at the Astrodome in Houston.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday, a lawyer for Holmes, due $3.6 million, sent a letter
to Levitt exercising a clause that gives the promoter a five-day
window to deliver. Foreman, 49, is owned $9 million.
</P>
<P>
Levitt said he believed the letters of credit would be sent
by Thursday. Holmes, asked if he though the fight would happen,
replied:"I don't know, man. What do you think?"
</P>
<P>
Foreman already has received a non-refundable $1 million down
payment.
</P>
<P>
"If Levitt comes in late with the letters of credit, I will
still do the fight," Foreman said.
</P>
<P>
Levitt said an investor pulled out a couple of weeks ago
after the Mike Tyson-Frans Botha fight, scheduled for January 16,
was announced, which would hurt Foreman-Holmes pay-per-view
sales. He said he notified Foreman's lawyer Henry Holmes last
week.
</P>
<P>
"We told him we would be five dayslate," Levitt said. "We had
to replace that investor. I'm as much a victim because I've put
in a million dollars. There's no big deal about this. The fight
is full tream ahead." 
</P>
