<HEADLINE> USOC Leader Promises Probe to Be Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Former Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, who opened the United States Olympic
Committee's investigation Tuesday into the scandal surrounding
Salt Lake City's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games,
pledged to "encourage, enhance and live up to" the Olympic ideal.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to attempt to pass judgment without knowing the
full facts," Mitchell said here. "The very purpose of the
commission is to try to get the facts and to make cetain that if,
in fact,there were practices in the past which were inappropriate
we'll do everything we can to prevent them from occurring in the
future."
</P>
<P>
Mitchell's five-member commission will investigate reports
that in 1989 Salt Lake Organizing Committee officials used more
than $400,000 worth of gifts, scholarships and other favors to
influence votes of International Olympic Committee officials who
select the location of the Games.
</P>
<P>
The commission also will recommend changes to the process in
which cities compete to become the U.S. candidate to host the
Olympic and Pan American games.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell said the commission will report its findings by
February 28. 
</P>
