<HEADLINE> Northeast China City Builds Home for Manchurian Tigers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Manchurian tigers have come
back to the Shenyang area of northeast China's Liaoning Province
after an absence of for 275 years.
</P>
<P>
Ten tigers are now living in the newly opened 50-hectare tiger
park, located in the Huishan Scenic Zone near the city of
Shenyang, capital of Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
The ten tigers, four males and six females, came to the park 20
days ago from a Manchurian-tiger breeding center in Hengdaohezi in
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that Shenyang was once a place where
Manchurian tigers could be found on every mountain in the area.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xinchen, an expert at the breeding center, said
there are fewer than 200 Manchurian tigers left in the world, and only
about 30 of them remain in the wild.
</P>
<P>
Liu, who began breeding Manchurian tigers eight years ago, said
that his breeding center has now bred some 110 Manchurian tigers.
</P>
</TEXT>
