<HEADLINE> Shanghai Establishes "Labor Service Bank" to Aid Old Folks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- China's leading industrial
city of Shanghai, with a population of 3 million elderly people,
has established a "labor service bank" to aid its aging population.
</P>
<P>
This plan stipulates that anyone who takes care of an elderly
person for a certain period of time can receive the same services
from others for equal hours when it is needed.
</P>
<P>
Sun Jialan, a 66-year-old woman, takes care a 73-year-old
neighbor lady for one hour a day, and for this she has "deposited"
close to 100 service hours in the "labor service bank" established
by the Tilanqiao Neighborhood Committee.
</P>
<P>
She said, "I can help others when I am able to do something and
I do not worry much about my future when I need help from others."
</P>
<P>
The "labor service bank," established this September, has
attracted 39 healthy "depositors" under 70.
</P>
<P>
Feng Xigen, head of the office in charge of elderly affairs
of the Tilanqiao Neighborhood Committee, said the establishment of the
bank is aimed at encouraging people to take care of the aged
and receive the same service in return when they grow older.
</P>
<P>
The number of people over 60 years old now accounts for at
least 20 percent of Shanghai's total population.  
</P>
</TEXT>
