<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agents Lament NBA Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The NBA lockout has been
six months today, and the sides are still fighting without signs
of putting it to an end.
</P>
<P>
The players held a conference call with union leadership,
three agents held a call with the media.
</P>
<P>
"This whole negotiation has been disgraceful," agnet Keith
Glass said. "I don't care if they have a season or they don't,
but this is not a game. And this has been treated as a game by
the league. There's an awful lot of people -- and I'm not talking
about owners, players or agents -- who have been hurt by this."
</P>
<P>
Three agents who represent 33 locked-out NBA players said
that no more than seven of their clients would vote for the
league's "final" offer to avoid cancelation of the season on
January 7, if it were put to a vote by their union's full
membership, as Commissioner David Stern suggested Monday.
</P>
<P>
Jerome Stanley said his five clients would reject the
proposed deal, Glass said all but "two or three" of his 10
clients would do likewise and Steve Kauffman said all but "three
or four" of his 18 clients would vote against it.
</P>
<P>
If the league's "final" offer were put to a union-wide vote,
"I don't think it would get 80 to 85 percent rejection rate as
Billy Hunter said, but I think a majority of players would reject
it," said Kauffman.
</P>
<P>
Another agent, Mark Bartelstein, said that none of his 25
clients would vote in favor of the owners' proposal. All of his
clients are in the middle-to-low end of the salary spectrum.
</P>
<P>
Stern was still in Aspen, and deputy commissioner Russ Granik
was in Florida with his family. Union director Hunter conducted a
conference call with players from his office in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
The league says it has made its final offer, and no further
talks are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
New Jersey star Jayson Williams joined Toronto's Kevin Willis
in calling for a secret vote of players.
</P>
<P>
"Let's have a secret vote," Williams said. "This would
strenthen our union. Billy Hunter, the union, the press and the
league would all know where the players stand.
</P>
<P>
I have the best job in the world, and two pepole ruined it
for me -- David Stern and Billy Hunter. Who cares about the NBA
anymore? I don't. I'm just like Joe Public," said Williams.
</P>
<P>
"I'm ashamed to be an NBA player right now. We are really
looking like a bunch of dumb athletes and a dumb league if you
can't split $2 billion."
</P>
<P>
The three agnets, who spoke on a conference call arranged by
the union, said the players made huge concessions.
</P>
<P>
"No matter where the thing ends, the league is going to end
up with a good, a very good deal, almost a dream deal," Stanley
said. "If you took the same deal and offered it to baseball and
football owners, they'd hop all over it.
</P>
<P>
"At what point does it become enough? At one point do the own
ers stand up to their negotiator and say, 'We've already gotten
enough. Let's move forward.'" 
</P>
</TEXT>
