<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Economic Index Rises in U.S. in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 30 (Xinhua) -- November leading economic
indicators in the U.S. point to a continuing growth through at
least early 1999, and the economy shows no evidence of cyclical
imbalance, a research group said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The New York-based Conference Board said in its monthly report
that its composite index of the leading economic indicators rose
0.6 percent in November at 106.3 (1992=100), compared to a growth
of 0.1 percent in October and a drop of 0.1 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
The index foresees economic activity six to nine months in
advance. The newest figures represent the highest rise since it
moved up 0.8 percent in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The leading indicators show real strength as we end the year,"
said Michael Boldin, Director of Business Cycle Research at the
Conference Board, an influential private research group.
</P>
<P>
"While increases of this size will probably not continue, it is
unlikely that we will see any serious retrenchments in the next
few months," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
