<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldova Lost 100,000 Ha of Forest in Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 30 (Xinhua) -- In the last five years,
100,000 hectares of wood have been destroyed in the Republic of
Moldova, causing an alarming decrease of the wildlife, according a
recent declaration of the Ecological Movement of Moldova (EMM).
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Garaba, an EMM expert, warned that Moldova has
recorded the poorest biodiversity development in Europe. According
to him, the small territory occupied by woods and high level of
field utilization caused the disappearance of tens of animal
species.
</P>
<P>
Moldova is one of the least forest-covered country in Europe,
affirmed Dionisie Boaghie, a leader of the non-government
organization Progresul Silvic (forest progress).
</P>
<P>
According to him, Moldova has a forest reserve of 394,400
hectares of planted areas, including 325,400 hectares of forests.
40 percent of this surface does not correspond to environmental
requirements, Boaghie stressed.
</P>
<P>
Vasile Mahu, director of the state-run association MoldSilva,
said that little has been done in the recent years to enlarge the
forest reserves. If in 1981 there was planted a surface of 7,000
hectares, this year the figure hardly showed 1,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists insist on elaboration of a special program
for forest protection and regeneration, which would be financed by
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Valentin Bobeico, deputy minister of environment, told the
media that the ministry is working on a national strategy of
forest and biological diversity protection, which is to be
presented to the government next February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981231.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
