<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End 1998 With Weak Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- All the three main European
stock markets drifted lower to a quiet close in shortened trading
Wednesday, the final session.
</P>
<P>
In London, the stock market ended its session of the year with
a headlong dive into the red.
</P>
<P>
With trading extremely thin as traders awaited the launch of
the euro Friday, the market opened almost unchanged.
</P>
<P>
But dangerous volatility soon set in and within an hour the
FTSE-100 Index had begun a downward surge. At one point it had
lost 132.5 point. The index finally closed down 58.9 points at
5,882.6.
</P>
<P>
The market seemed unaffected by Tuesday's rally on Wall Street
which saw the Dow Jones close up 98.23 points.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt an initial rise of 1 percent was wiped out in
moribund trading, as the Xetra Dax index of leading shares closed
down 0.73 percent at 5,019.23.
</P>
<P>
Siemens AG, which set about major restructuring in 1998, was
among leading decliners, falling 5.25 marks to 107.50 although in
extremely low volume.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 was equally downbeat, with most traders
concentrating on the impact of Thursday's conversion from francs
to euros.
</P>
<P>
One trader said, "There is some nostalgia about it being the
last day of trading in francs, but really, no one is interested in
doing any business."
</P>
<P>
"At the moment, most people are thinking about Monday and
beginning to wonder about how the prices will look in euros. Few
are really interested in what happens today," another trader said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
