<HEADLINE> Business Failures Show First Rise Since 1992 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The first annual increase in
business failures in Britain since 1992 was recorded, with a 6.2
percent rise in failed companies since last year.
</P>
<P>
The figures by business information company Dun &AMP; Bradstreet
released Wednesday show that nearly 200 more businesses are
failing each month than at the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 38,634 businesses went to the wall, compared with
36,368 in 1997 -- an increase of 2,266.
</P>
<P>
"The collapse of world markets, and the strong pound are the
main contributors," said Philip Mellor, analyst at Dun &AMP;
Bradstreet.
</P>
<P>
"You have had company start-ups failing as you would in good
times, but their problems have been compounded," he added.
</P>
<P>
A separate report shows the number of management buy-outs and
buy-ins going into receivership in 1998 hit its highest level
since 1995, with 62 companies affected, according to the Center
for Management Buy Out Research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
