<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Launches VAT System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The implementation of the
Value Added Tax (VAT), a new tax system introduced by the
Government to enhance the country's revenue base, took off
Wednesday without much anxiety.
</P>
<P>
The VAT, which replaces the sales and service taxes is pegged
at 10 percent as compared with 15 percent charged under the old
system.
</P>
<P>
It was first introduced in 1995 at a rate of 17.5 percent but
was withdrawn three and a half months later following public
outcry and demonstrations on price distortions.
</P>
<P>
The re-introduction had been preceded by a public education
campaign and appropriate legal framework to support it as these
were some of the reasons for the withdrawal in 1995.
</P>
<P>
But critics have argued against the implementation of the new
tax regime, saying education on it was not elaborate enough.
</P>
<P>
Under the new VAT, the minimum turnover of businesses
qualified to charge VAT was also raised to 200 million Cedis (one
U.S. Dollar equals to some 2,350 Cedis) as against 25 million in
1995, perhaps to cut off petty traders and "corner shops", which
complicated the computation of the tax under the previous system.
</P>
<P>
Unlike before, most shoppers went round the virtually quiet
city shops without even noticing the switch over to the new tax.
</P>
<P>
"For me, it is the same old prices and if the change is not
going to be significant, then why worry," Yaw Tuga Yeboah, who
shopped from the Multi-Stores said.
</P>
<P>
Prices in most of the shops, which have boldly displayed their
VAT Certificate, indicating their authority to charge VAT on
their goods, have not changed from the pre-Christmas levels.
</P>
<P>
This may be the reason why consumers have not paid much
attention to the VAT and are not also worried about the new tax.
</P>
<P>
Some businesses, even though by the nature of their operations
could qualify to charge VAT, are still not registered.
</P>
<P>
The reason, they say, is that they are below the VAT
threshold.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the VAT law allows for voluntary registration, which
permits businesses below the 200 million-Cedi threshold to
register and operate VAT.
</P>
<P>
So far, over 7,000 traders have been issued with VAT
certificates throughout the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
