<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Yeltsin Agree to Disagree Over Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Russian President Boris Yeltsin Wednesday agreed to disagree
over U.S. air strikes against Iraq so that the two countries could
move the common agenda forward in 1999, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called Yeltsin from the Oval Office before leaving on a
New Year's vacation in South Carolina, White House spokesman David
Leavy said. They talked about 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"Both presidents agreed that despite differences over Iraq, it
was important to continue to build the U.S.-Russian relationship
and to move the important common agenda that we have forward in
1999," Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has strongly criticized U.S.-British bombings against
Iraq on Dec. 16-19, insisting there was no justification for using
force.
</P>
<P>
During their phone conversation, Yeltsin "stated his views, but
the president (Clinton) explained why force was necessary," Leavy
said.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time Clinton and Yeltsin had spoken since U.S.
and British air strikes against Iraq targets.
</P>
<P>
Leavy said Yeltsin did not specifically mention incidents
Monday and Wednesday in which U.S. warplanes and Iraqi air defense
batteries in northern and southern Iraq exchanged fires. But
Clinton referred to the incidents and stressed his determination
to enforce the no-fly zones, established right after the Gulf War
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Clinton expressed "concern about the continuing threat that
Saddam poses" in the Gulf region, Leavy said, and told Yeltsin
that "allied air crews will take the necessary precautions to
protect themselves and carry out their mission."
</P>
<P>
Leavy also said the conversation was mostly about items other
than Iraq, including the START II nuclear arms accord that awaits
Russian approval before taking effect; plans for meeting between
Vice President Al Gore and Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov in
March and the meeting between Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
"Both stressed there is a solid foundation for the relationship
and agreed there is a need to tackle all the important issues for
1999," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton reiterated U.S. support for economic reform in Russia.
He thanked Yeltsin for his New Year's message and extended New
Year greetings to the Russian people, Leavy said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
