<HEADLINE> Greece's Opposition Party Leader Criticizes Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The leader of Greece's main
opposition party New Democracy, Costas Karamanlis, Wednesday
criticized the decision by Nicosia and Athens regarding the
deployment of the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
After consultations with Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
and Cyprus' National Council of political leaders, Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides Tuesday announced the cancellation of
plans to install the missiles in the divided island republic and
to negotiate their possible deployment in the southern Greek
island of Crete.
</P>
<P>
Simitis expressed his full support for Clerides' decision and
called it a responsible decision which would promote Cyprus'
defense and protection.
</P>
<P>
While describing the decision as "a grave defeat," Karamanlis
said in a statement that the consequences of incoherence, lack of
credibility and concessions were most serious for the whole of
Hellenism.
</P>
<P>
He said that all Greeks could not be called on to pay each time
for the serious mistakes of governments which proved themselves
less than able to meet the challenge.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government's handling of the missile issue
illustrated the need for a national strategy with the greatest
possible consensus and participation of all the country's
political forces, the party leader said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
