<HEADLINE> Rwanda's Economic Growth Tops 12% in Four Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan economy has
experienced a steady growth of 12 percent in the past four years,
said Minister of Finance and Economic Planning Donald Kaberuka
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Its economy is performing at 90 percent of its pre-war
capacity in just four years, Kaberuka was quoted by the
Independent Rwanda News Agency (RNA) as saying Wednesday in a
special story, which sent to Xinhua based in Nairobi here.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that when Rwanda emerged out of the 1994 civil
war, its economy was in total shambles, and its GDP had dropped
to about 50% of what it was before the war and the genocide.
</P>
<P>
Kaberuka said that this growth is not a surprise for any
economy beginning at Zero and it is quite normal to post such
growth rates, because the Rwandan government notably exercised
much fiscal and macro-economic discipline and closely followed
guidelines laid down by the donor community.
</P>
<P>
There are no longer any controls on foreign exchange rates,
and interests rates are freely determined in the country, said
Kaberuka.
</P>
<P>
Kaberuka said the government brought inflation -- which
constitutes a major obstacle to recovering economies -- almost
under control by basically living within the country's means and
desisting from measures like printing money.
</P>
<P>
The latest economic report of the country for 1998 covering
the period up to October, showed that the agriculture sector,
which represents 37 percent of the GDP and employs 91 percent of
the labor force, has now reached 86 percent of the normal
production.
</P>
<P>
The industry sector, which represents about 25 percent of the
GDP and occupies two percent of the labor force, has registered a
recovery estimated at 78 percent of its pre-war production.
</P>
<P>
Minister Kaberuka laid a special emphasis on the poverty
rocking the small central African state of Rwanda, where 70
percent of the population live below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan government has just adopted a national development
strategy for the next two decades -- ending in the year 2020 --
which hinges on the modernization of agriculture, the development
of human resources, especially in science, technology and
management.
</P>
<P>
Other areas targeted by the new strategy include the
development of the country's infrastructure, the development of
transport infrastructure, notably the construction of railways to
link Rwanda with the Ocean outlet in a bid to lower high costs of
imports, and the promotion of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Although Rwanda has embarked on privatizing most of its
cumbersome enterprises and is progressively getting out of
commercial activities, the privatization drive has not been
welcomed by business people, and trade unions.
</P>
<P>
According to Kaberuka, Rwanda hopes to garner more revenues by
initiating an ambitious program of selling off a number of
government buildings and houses, and giving an impetus to the
privatization drive.
</P>
<P>
He deplored that Rwanda has been forsaken by donors because of
his involvement in the Congo (K) war.
</P>
<P>
It is unfair for donor agencies to punish a country doing its
best to implement and carry out its program, Kaberuka said
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
