<HEADLINE> Ghanaians Flee Cote d'Ivoire for Fishing Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Ghanaian Authorities have
evacuated home some 600 Ghanaians including 342 children fleeing
communal violence in Sassandra, an Ivorian fishing village, some
285 kilometers from the commercial capital, Abidjan.
</P>
<P>
Seven Ghanaians were killed and a great number wounded during
the violence which was sparked off by an alleged drowning of an
Ivorian at sea during a scuffle over fishing rights.
</P>
<P>
The Ghanaians, mostly fishermen and their family members,
arrived at the Western border town of Elubo and were transported
in waiting buses to Komenda, Elmina, Moree and Mankessim, all in
the tourist region of central Ghana, a special story by Ghanaian
News Agency (GNA) faxed to Xinhua here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Fighting broke out when Ivorian fishermen returning from sea
alleged that a Ghanaian fishing group sank their boat during the
scuffle, resulting in drowning one of their colleagues, whose
body they are yet to recover.
</P>
<P>
There were some 3,000 Ghanaians living in Sassandra before the
violence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ivorian government has pledged 500,000 CFA
francs (some 840 U.S. Dollars) to each of the bereaved families
of the seven Ghanaian fishermen killed in the violence.
</P>
<P>
It is also providing resources for the rebuilding of their
houses destroyed during the fighting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
